m\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Early on a hot morning in the impoverished township of Diepsloot, a dozen figures in orange overalls tend a field of beetroot, cabbage and lettuce, the silence broken only by the clink of hoes and shovels. For most, it is the first regular work that they have done for years.\par \par \uc2 The labourers are among 97,000 people employed under the Community Work Programme, set up by charitable groups in 2009. In July, the government identified the CWP as an important part of the fight against unemployment, and promised to give it sufficient funding to reach 1m participants by 2014.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Partly because of its weak education system, South Africa's unemployment rate is among the highest in the world. Jacob Zuma has identified job creation as a priority, but the economy has shed jobs since he became president in 2009, particularly among younger people.\par \par \uc2 This year, the government launched a R9bn "jobs fund", aimed at creating 150,000 work places over three years. However, some government policies - such as a wage subsidy for unemployed youths - have been opposed by the influential trade unions, which voice concern for the job security of existing workers.\par \par \uc2 Government support for the CWP will allow it to expand the reach of its projects, which offer workers eight days' work a month, for a modest stipend of R60 ($7.60) a day. Those who perform well can be promoted to a full-time role, offering about R1,800 a month.\par \par \uc2 The focus is on work that benefits poor communities: assisting teachers in crowded schools, producing food for the needy, or delivering drugs to HIV/Aids sufferers.\par \par \uc2 The workers at Diepsloot, north of Johannesburg, speak of a sense of renewed pride, both in themselves and in their community. The township sprang up in the late 1990s, as poor people sought work in the prosperous nearby suburb of Fourways, and is now one of the most impoverished urban areas in the country. CWP projects in Diepsloot, employ about 900 people.\par \par \uc2 "If I didn't do this, I wouldn't be doing anything," says Nicholas Motaung, 24, on a break from cleaning a local clinic. "If I keep working here and marketing myself, I think I'll find a permanent job."\par \par \uc2 The goal of "making people more employable" is central to the CWP, says Caroline O'Reilly, a director of Teba Development, one of two agencies that oversee the programme at a national level.\par \par \uc2 The CWP's organisers hope to attract the attention of \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  schemes. \uc2 Old Mutual\uc2 , the insurance group, has been sending teams to train participants in managing their finances, but has not yet been joined by other large companies.\par \par \uc2 Ms O'Reilly emphasises that the projects should not be seen as offering long-term employment, and must work in tandem with permanent job creation by both the private and public sectors. "It's not a job; it's a safety net," Ms O'Reilly says.\par \par \uc2 Nonetheless, a lack of permanent opportunities means that some of those on the projects expect to be involved with them for years. Few in South Africa predict a rapid improvement in the country's damagingly high youth unemployment rate of about 50 per cent - a "ticking time bomb", according to Kgalema Motlanthe, deputy president.\par \par \uc2 Yet the low level of wages on offer puts many urban youths off the CWP, and most of the workers at Diepsloot - while grateful for any extra income - complain that the daily wage should be higher.\par \par \uc2 Ms O'Reilly defends the low wage. "The more you raise the allowance, the fewer people you can employ in the projects," she says.\par \par \uc2 Dennis Dykes, chief economist at Nedbank, says that the CWP will help to address the "key problem" of unemployed people who have no experience of the workplace.\par \par \uc2 However, he criticises the government for doing too little to boost job creation in the private sector. "It's not addressing the overall business \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  and creating confidence and stability within that sector," he says.\par \par \uc2 "And until they do that, you're not going to see strong employment growth."\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 e1116 : \uc2 Employment/Unemployment | e11 : \uc2 Economic Performance/Indicators | ecat : \uc2 Economic News\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b IPC\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 CN | GN | CN11 | CN1105\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15