not cut and paste FT articles and redistribute by email or post to the web.   \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Formula One's popular image is all about raw speed and engine power, achieved at any cost - be that money, fuel or exhaust fumes.\par \par \uc2 But behind the scenes, the sport has been working hard to make its cars and practices much greener. Three years from now, a new set of rules will take effect aimed at significantly cutting the sport's carbon footprint.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 The centrepiece of the new technical regulations, which will take effect from 2014, is a shift from 2.4litre V8 engines to smaller 1.6litre V6 engines. Cars will be required to race with 35 per cent less fuel on board. They will no longer be able to roar into the pit lane, but will be required to use electric power instead.\par \par \uc2 According to a study of the sport's environmental impact commissioned by the Formula One Teams Association (Fota) and conducted by Trucost, the consultancy, the 215,588 tonnes of CO2 emitted by F1 teams in 2009 made up only a small proportion of the sport's total carbon footprint. The bulk of this came from things such as raw materials, parts, electricity and travel.\par \par \uc2 So, away from the track, teams are taking other measures to cut carbon emissions, ranging from the design of their factories and the paint they use on cars to the size of the teams and the use of air freight.\par \par \uc2 Pressure to cut emissions comes both from within the teams themselves, and from sponsors mindful of their place on \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  league tables.\par \par \uc2 "We have seen the sport move from [the sponsorship] being dominated largely by the tobacco industry [until this was banned in 2005] to large automotive firms, high-technology businesses and some financial institutions," according to Jonathan Neale, managing director of \uc2 McLaren Racing\uc2 , one of F1's leading teams. "All of those organisations have boards of directors who expect everyone who they are associated with to resonate with their corporate values."\par \par \uc2 In this context, running unrestricted V8 engines will not do anymore. "The perception is as important to manage as the core subject," Mr Neale says.\par \par \uc2 Alongside other Fota members, McLaren has worked to reduce the size of its operating teams and technicians - now down to 47, compared with as many as 60 before. \uc2 Vodafone\uc2 , its sponsor, has helped the team with its communications, keeping members connected and reducing the number that need to travel to races.\par \par \uc2 The drive to make F1 greener is not new. The 2009 season saw the introduction of kinetic energy recovery, a hybrid system that gives cars an extra 80 horsepower for six or seven seconds at the push of a button.\par \par \uc2 To a cynical eye, the push to clean up an inherently high-octane sport smacks of "greenwashing".\par \par \uc2 However, participants say the greener ethos is more than just a ploy for better public relations.\par \par \uc2 Rather, they insist it is essential to the sport's continuing survival because it dovetails with the car industry's overriding technological priority of the moment: carbon reduction.\par \par \uc2 Manufacturers Honda, Toyota, and \uc2 BMW\uc2  all dropped their involvement in F1 during the financial crisis after concluding the sport was not a core activity. Even before the credit crunch, many manufacturers admitted the direct synergies between their motorsport and volume-car engineering programmes were limited.\par \par \uc2 However, Ferrari, the Italian manufacturer, has what it describes as a "long tradition" of transferring technology from F1 to its high-end road cars. Features derived from racing include steering wheel-mounted gear-shift paddles, vehicle aerodynamics and its cars' F1-Trac traction control.\par \par \uc2 At last year's Geneva motor show, Ferrari showed off its advanced lightweight hybrid car to demonstrate how it was transferring cleaner F1 technology to its road cars. The car's colour - lest anyone miss the point - was not Ferrari's traditional red, but vibrant green.\par \par \uc2 Renault sold its team this year, but remains in F1 as an engine supplier to about a third of the grid, including Red Bull Racing and Team Lotus.\par \par \uc2 However, whether to stay in the sport at all was a "question mark" for Renault's board, the company's F1 boss insists. Renault, he says, did so only after successfully pushing the FIA to draft new rules requiring smaller engines. "We took the decision to stay in F1 only if the new engine was relevant and the new regulation was relevant," says Jean-Fran\u231\'00\'E7ois Caubet, head of Renault's F1 engine programme.\par \par \uc2 In its mass-market car business, Renault is pursuing CO2 reduction as a priority, he explains. The company believes that by late this decade, most of the engines the industry produces for road cars will be downsized, many with turbocharging or electric power.\par \par \uc2 Renault's F1 engines are built at its technical centre near Paris, with engineers typically spending three years there before moving to the carmaker's mainstream engineering centre.\par \par \uc2 According to Mr Caubet, the engine programme has a budget of about \u8364\'20\'AC120m ($165m). The net cost to the company, after accounting for the unit's sponsorship and supply revenues, is \u8364\'20\'AC60m - a reasonable price, he says, for the public relations windfall of having supplied engines to the winning team. "For \u8364\'20\'AC60m, you have a big exposure in the world," he says.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 gmora : \uc2 Motor Racing | gmoto : \uc2 Motor Sports | gspo : \uc2 Sports/Recreation | ncat : \uc2 Content Types | nfact : \uc2 Factiva Filters | nfce : \uc2 FC&E Exclusion Filter | nrgn : \uc2 Routine General News\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b PUB\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 The Financial Times Limited (AAIW/EIW)\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clv