li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Agriculture\par \par \uc2 Michiyo Nakamoto finds progress in the sector is slow\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Seiyo, a rural town of just over 42,000 residents on the southwestern island of Shikoku in Japan, prides itself on its diversified geography and varied climate, which allow the local farming community to grow everything from mandarin oranges and rice to chestnuts and grapes.\par \par \uc2 But Seiyo has a problem - 65 per cent of its farmers are aged 65 or older.\par \par \uc2 The town is not unique in a country where the population has been greying for many years but as its farming population ages, Japan is under mounting pressure to improve productivity in its agricultural sector.\par \par \uc2 The need to raise productivity is all the more pressing as the government prepares to join the TransPacific Partnership, a trade agreement, which could further open the country's agricultural markets to imports from highly competitive producers.\par \par \uc2 The agricultural sector's sales are currently Y4,700bn ($60bn), which is close to the revenues generated by Fujitsu, the technology services group, Risaburo Nezu, a senior executive fellow at the Fujitsu Research Institute, points out.\par \par \uc2 "Yet there are 3m farmers, or 20 times more than Fujitsu employees; in other words, agricultural productivity is a 20th of Fujitsu's," Mr Nezu says.\par \par \uc2 In the US and Australia, where large-scale farms often span hundreds of hectares, there has been a trend towards precision farming. This makes use of advanced information technology to improve productivity by managing variations in soils, plant growth and yield.\par \par \uc2 It has enabled farmers not only to increase productivity, but to do so while decreasing production costs and environmental impact.\par \par \uc2 "It may be said that agriculture is undergoing a sort of revolution, from dependence on manual labour, to the 'informatisation' of farming," says Satoshi Hirano, general manager of the positioning business unit at Topcon, a leading Japanese maker of surveying instruments.\par \par \uc2 Topcon's advanced guidance and autosteering systems, which allow farmers to guide and run machines automatically according to preset patterns; or its seed rate controller, which can control or monitor the sowing of seeds or spraying of pesticides, for example, are predominantly sold outside Japan.\par \par \uc2 The country has been a laggard in the adoption of information technology and most farmers still rely on experience and instinct.\par \par \uc2 The prevalence of small lots cultivated by independent farmers, and a general resistance, particularly by co-operatives, to changing their ways, have proved to be strong obstacles to the modernisation of agriculture.\par \par \uc2 But there is a growing recognition that Japan needs to consolidate its small and scattered farms and adopt more advanced methods.\par \par \uc2 One initiative to improve productivity is being taken by Japanese businesses in Saijyo, also on Shikoku.\par \par \uc2 This summer, \uc2 Sumitomo Chemical\uc2  set up a trial farm to experiment with ad-vanced technology in an exercise aimed at finding ways of improving the profitability of agriculture.\par \par \uc2 The Sunrise Farm project has the backing of Keidanren, the big-business lobby, which is headed by \uc2 Sumitomo Chemical\uc2 's chairman, as well as the local industrial promotion organisation and the local agricultural co-operative.\par \par \uc2 The farm, which spans 5 hectares, planted its first lettuce seedlings in an "ecological" greenhouse. Here the company is able to control the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  better than if the seedlings were grown in an open field.\par \par \uc2 Although the seedlings were grown in the heat of August, it was possible to keep temperatures in the greenhouse much lower by spraying water over the greenhouse, which is covered with a special film to raise efficiency, explains Masahiro Tamaki, manager of \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  and sales in Sumitomo's domestic crop protection division.\par \par \uc2 To reduce the temperature further, the farm will employ the MH freezer system, which acts like an air conditioner but uses much less electricity.\par \par \uc2 The key feature of the system is that it uses only hot and cold waste energy such as exhaust heat from industrial facilities, and groundwater or rivers.\par \par \uc2 Sunrise Farm will also use agricultural technology that is common in the west, including driverless tractors and internet cameras to enable farmers to monitor the condition of crops remotely.\par \par \uc2 The project will not be restricted to farming, but will utilise advanced refrigeration technology to maintain the freshness of the produce, and chips to collect data for reference and traceability.\par \par \uc2 "This project is aimed at developing a total system to allow farmers to profit from each stage of the production, distribution and sales of their produce," says Takayuki Nagakubo, manager of the agribusiness planning team at Sumitomo.\par \par \uc2 "We want to develop a business model that will allow farmers to be profitable," he adds.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\tr