justright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Until recently I thought \uc2 Unilever\uc2  was a company whose primary purpose was to make products such as shampoo. No longer. Last week I chaired a panel of business leaders on the sidelines of the World Economic Forum in Davos. During that debate, entitled "The Future of Business", it became clear that most business leaders do not want to talk about grubby financial realities these days, or, at least, not at Davos.\par \par \uc2 Instead, \uc2 Keith Weed\uc2 , \uc2 Unilever\uc2 's head of marketing, earnestly outlined the social and environmental initiatives the company was pursuing to help consumers. Whereas \uc2 Unilever\uc2  used to think of \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  as separate from core business, he said, these days CSR was at the core of everything it does.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Novartis\uc2 , the pharmaceutical group, is likewise devoting considerable energy to bringing health initiatives to poor people, even at a loss. \uc2 Daniel Vasella\uc2 , its chairman, told the panel this made him "very proud". T.K. Kurien, the head of Wipro, the Indian technology group, said his company was also expanding its social programmes in response to employee demand. These companies are not alone: a senior employee at Bloomberg revealed that CSR pages are now one of the fastest-growing sections of its data terminals. Investors are apparently clamouring for information about companies' CSR programmes, be that in relation to "responsible" shampoo - or anything else.\par \par \uc2 Is this a good thing? Some think it is. Nadine Hack, executive-in-residence at IMD business school in Lausanne, believes that companies should be applauded for being more socially engaged. After all, she argues, companies are so powerful these days that there is little hope of addressing societal problems without their support. Conversely, when corporate muscle is engaged, it can be powerful: when \uc2 Coca-Cola\uc2  started battling Aids in Africa, it had an extraordinary impact.\par \par \uc2 But there is a strong counter-argument: that companies would do better to focus on their primary function - making money - and leave governments to worry about social goals. Governments are elected to make countries better, so why do unelected company executives feel any duty to reach into other areas of life? "The fact that companies are doing all this CSR stuff just shows that government has failed," muttered one British executive.\par \par \uc2 My views lie somewhere between these extremes: I think that companies should recognise their wider impact but I also think that it is primarily up to governments to set the rules and pursue wider social aims. I don't want \uc2 Unilever\uc2  to trash the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  with high-margin shampoo but I expect the government, not \uc2 Unilever\uc2 , to set environmental standards, penalise miscreants - and tax \uc2 Unilever\uc2  to help the poor.\par \par \uc2 But whatever anybody thinks of CSR, my experience of Davos suggests its importance can only grow right now. That is partly because governments are failing to pursue many of their core responsibilities, forcing companies to step in. But a second, related, factor is that company executives are getting scared of wider social strains. For example, a survey from the World Economic Forum showed that "income disparity" heads the list of issues that Davos Man thinks will threaten global stability this year. That is stunning, since income disparity never even featured on that list until this year.\par \par \uc2 Corporate executives do not have any easy answers. As Mr Kurien observed: "We [in business] can all see the problem of income disparity, we just don't know what to do about it." But in today's world they need to be seen to be doing something. Hence the appeal of CSR; it has become a useful salve for a troubled corporate conscience, if not a quasi-amulet that companies wear as protection against future social strife.\par \par \uc2 And along the way, CSR is delivering some genuine good - at least, I fervently hope so. Either way, it provides something else to ponder the next time you buy a bottle of shampoo. \u61494\'F0\'36\par \par \uc2 gillian.tett@ft.com\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CO\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 ulvr : \uc2 Unilever PLC | wecof : \uc2 World Economic Forum | unifl : \uc2 Unilever NV\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b IN\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 i41 : \uc2 Food/Beverages/Tobacco\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpa