t\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CY\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2012 The New York Times Company. All rights reserved   \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 to add more details throughout.\par \par \uc2 Responding to a growing outcry over conditions at its overseas factories, \uc2 Apple\uc2  said Monday that an outside organization had begun to audit working conditions at the plants where the bulk of iPhones, iPads and other \uc2 Apple\uc2  products are built, and that the group would make its finding public.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 For years, \uc2 Apple\uc2  has resisted calls for independent scrutiny of the suppliers that make its electronics. But for the first time it has begun publicly divulging information that it once considered secret, after criticism that included coordinated protests last week at \uc2 Apple\uc2  stores around the world and investigative news reports about punishing conditions inside some factories.\par \par \uc2 Last month, \uc2 Apple\uc2  released the names of 156 of its suppliers.\u160\'00\'A0Two weeks later, \uc2 Apple\uc2 's chief executive sent an e-mail to the company's 65,000 employees defending \uc2 Apple\uc2 's manufacturing record while also pledging to go "deeper into the supply chain." And now, the company has asked an outside group - a nonprofit financed partly by participating companies like \uc2 Apple\uc2  - to publicly identify specific factories where abuses are discovered.\par \par \uc2 Corporate analysts say \uc2 Apple\uc2 's shifts could incite widespread changes throughout the electronics industry, since a lot of companies use the same suppliers. They also said it seemed calculated to forestall the kind of public relations problems over labor issues that in previous decades afflicted companies like \uc2 Nike\uc2 , Gap and \uc2 Disney\uc2 . "This is a really big deal," said Sasha Lezhnev at the Enough Project, a group focused on corporate accountability. "The whole industry has to follow whatever \uc2 Apple\uc2  does."\par \par \uc2 But it is unclear if the efforts by \uc2 Apple\uc2 , whose $469 billion market value is the largest of any company in the world, will be enough to quiet its critics, some of whom had urged \uc2 Apple\uc2  to work with Chinese monitoring organizations with direct knowledge of its suppliers in China.\par \par \uc2 Though some labor groups applauded Monday's announcement, others said that the outside auditor \uc2 Apple\uc2  chose, the Fair Labor Association, which is based in Washington, was not sufficiently independent. And some critics questioned whether the inspections - \uc2 Apple\uc2  said the manufacturers had agreed to do them voluntarily - would sharply curtail problems or merely help \uc2 Apple\uc2  deflect criticism.\par \par \uc2 "F.L.A. is part of a \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  industry that's totally compromised," said Judy Gearhart, executive director of the International Labor Rights Forum, an advocacy group for workers. "The auditing has been proven to be weak, and real solutions need a lot more than auditing. It takes empowering workers."\par \par \uc2 Apple\uc2 , in a statement, said that the Fair Labor Association was an independent organization that had been given "unrestricted access" to the company's suppliers. The first inspections, \uc2 Apple\uc2  said, were conducted on Monday at a factory in Shenzhen, China, known as Foxconn City, one of the largest plants within China. Human rights advocates have long said that Foxconn City's 230,000 employees are subjected to long hours, coerced overtime and harsh working conditions, all of which Foxconn disputes.\par \par \uc2 Apple\uc2  has said that if the companies manufacturing its products do not measure up to its labor and human rights standards, it will stop working with them.\par \par \uc2 "We have a very credible, independent monitoring system," said \uc2 Jorge Perez-Lopez\uc2 , executive director of the Fair Labor Association. "Yes, \uc2 Nike\uc2  is on our board. So are other companies. But so are universities. And our reports are written by staff, without consultation or influence."\par \par \uc2 Since 2007, \uc2 Apple\uc2  has released yearly audit reports of its own detailing labor violations and unsafe conditions at its suppliers. More than half of the facilities audited by \uc2 Apple\uc2  every year had violated at least one aspect of the company's supplier code of conduct, and in some instances violated the law.\par \par \uc2 Auditors have found instances of excessive overtime, underage workers, improperly disposed hazardous waste and falsified records, according to the company's reports. Two years ago, 137 workers at an \uc2 Apple\uc2  supplier in eastern China were injured after they were ordered to use a poisonous chemical to clean iPhone screens. Last year, two explosions at iPad factories killed four people and injured 77.\par \par \uc2 Working conditions at \uc2 Apple\uc2 's suppliers were the subject of articles published last month by The New York Times.\par \par \uc2 Because \uc2 Apple\uc2 's public disclosures of problems do not identify the suppliers by name, it is difficult to determine where specific abuses happened. It is also tough to determine if conditions improved after \uc2 Apple\uc2  demanded changes, as the company says. The company has disclosed little about its manufacturing process over all, at least partly because it does not want to tip off competitors.\par \par \uc2 For instance, Chinese advocacy groups - which are often considered reliable, independent monitors - have published multiple reports saying that Foxconn employees regularly work more than 12 hours a day, seven days a week, a violation of both Chinese law and \uc2 Apple\uc2 's code of conduct. \uc2 Apple\uc2  has audited Foxconn City multiple times and Foxconn, in a statement sent to The Times, said it had never been cited by \uc2 Apple\uc2  for overworked employees.\par \par \uc2 If the Fair Labor Association conducts wide-ranging audits and publishes data on specific facilities, it could transform the attention brought to the worst performers, and in the example of Foxconn City, help determine whether Foxconn, or the advocacy groups, have been telling the truth.\par \par \uc2 "The problem with the F.L.A. is that it lives by rules set up by the companies itself," said Mr. Lezhnev of the Enough Project. "Real transparency will transform the electronics industry. But if it's just a whitewash, I'm not sure how much will change."\par \par \uc2 Apple\uc2 , in its statement, said the Fair Labor Association's findings and recommendations from its first inspections would most likely be posted online in early March on the group's Web site, fairlabor.org.\par \par \uc2 At \uc2 Apple\uc2 's request, the group will also conduct audits of \uc2 Apple\uc2 's other main assembly factories, including Foxconn's plant in Chengdu and facilities run by Quanta and Pegatron, where the bulk of iPhones, iPads and other devices are made. Those and other plants also build goods for almost every other major electronics company, including Dell, \uc2 Hewlett-Packard\uc2 , I.B.M., Lenovo, \uc2 Motorola\uc2 , \uc2 Nokia\uc2 , \uc2 Sony\uc2 , \uc2 Toshiba\uc2  and others.\par \par \uc2 While other companies have been criticized for conditions at their operations overseas, \uc2 Apple\uc2  has received particular attention because it is the biggest - its market value is more than the combined value of \uc2 Google\uc2  and \uc2 Microsoft\uc2  - and among the richest. Its stock closed Monday at $502.60, up more than 20 percent this year. The company also has a vast overseas presence, with its contractors employing 700,000 people in China and elsewhere.\par \par \uc2 Apple\uc2  said Monday that its suppliers had pledged to give the auditors unrestricted access to their operations during the inspections. \uc2 Apple\uc2  said the organization would "interview thousands of employees about working and living conditions including health and safety, compensation, working hours and communication with management." It will also inspect manufacturing areas, worker dormitories and other facilities, the company said.\par \par \uc2 "We believe that workers everywhere have the right to a safe and fair work \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 , which is why we've asked the F.L.A. to independently assess the performance of our largest suppliers,"\uc2 Timothy D. Cook\uc2 , \uc2 Apple\uc2 's chief executive, said in a statement. "The inspections now under way are unprecedented in the electronics industry, both in scale and scope, and we appreciate the F.L.A. agreeing to take the unusual step of identifying the factories in their reports."\par \par \uc2 In January, \uc2 Apple\uc2  announced it would be the first technology company to join the Fair Labor Association. The organization was founded in 1999, and evolved out a task force created by PresidentBill Clinton and a handful of apparel and footwear companies - including \uc2 Nike\uc2  - to combat child labor and other abusive working conditions.\par \par \uc2 When completed, \uc2 Apple\uc2  said, the association's inspections will have covered factories where more than 90 percent of \uc2 Apple\uc2 's products are assembled.\par \par \uc2 * Daily Report: \uc2 Apple\uc2  Asks Outside Group to Inspect Factories\par \par \uc2 * Foxconn Resolves Pay Dispute With Workers\par \par \uc2 * Game That Critiques \uc2 Apple\uc2  Vanishes From \uc2 App Store\par \par \uc2 * Explosion at Foxconn Factory That Makes iPads\par \par \uc2 * \uc2 Apple\uc2  Says Chinese Supplier Made Changes After Suicides\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CO\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 applc : \uc2 Apple Inc\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b IN\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 i3302 : \uc2 Computers/Electroni