cles and redistribute by email or post to the web.   \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 European leaders have spent so much of the past four years staring into a series of economic and financial abysses that a deep, dark pessimism has entered the European soul. Even in the normally optimistic United States, business and political elites openly discuss the end of empire as if it was the end times.\par \par \uc2 Despite failures of political leadership on both sides of the Atlantic, many western businesses are doing rather well. Innovation in business models and products continues, productivity in the major economies is improving, profits are up, cash is being stockpiled.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 No wonder, then, that business leaders in the emerging markets to our east and south are still looking towards the west for examples of best practice in how companies should be managed and governed. The big business schools are setting up shop in emerging markets to teach business leadership and management. Associations like the UK's Institute of Directors are active on the ground. And emerging markets board directors are still looking to Europe and the US for rigorous models of corporate governance.\par \par \uc2 How long the west can retain this advantage remains to be seen as new models emerge in the rising markets from South Africa to Latin America, from the Middle East to South-East Asia.\par \par \uc2 I have recently spent time talking to board directors in four countries: India, Russia, Turkey and the UAE. The optimism and excitement in those markets is palpable.\par \par \uc2 Why the interest in corporate governance in these emerging markets? After all, the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  could be seen as quite inhospitable to the concept. The state still owns many businesses outright or with a controlling interest. Other large companies are run by large families. In the Middle East, there is little difference between state-owned and family-owned businesses.\par \par \uc2 To some academics and business leaders in places like India and UAE, corporate governance is important in and of itself, but it is also becoming more practically important as companies seek capital outside of their home countries. Emerging markets companies looking to build their brands through international expansion are often called upon to explain their approaches to environmental issues, \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  and governance matters. Poor governance often leads to lower equity valuations that are bad for partially public enterprises.\par \par \uc2 For many players in the emerging markets, the west itself still has powerful brand equity. An investor in Abu Dhabi told me, "Being based in the region doesn't give you better access or a better reputation. Value added comes from the west. If you are based here the perception would not be of the same high quality."\par \par \uc2 Despite the financial crisis and failure of many western banks, western companies are perceived to have more advanced corporate governance than their counterparts in the emerging markets. A board director in Turkey said, "We look for best practice outside. We need to import it."\par \par \uc2 Ironically, even bank directors in emerging markets look to western banks for lessons in risk management and internal control. Another Turkish director said, "If you set standards high, it's western Europe... Our main counterparties are London based, [emerging markets] banks with counterparties need western standards."\par \par \uc2 Perhaps it is more obvious for Turkish companies to look to Europe in particular, since the country is an aspirant member of the European Union. Another Turkish director told me, "Our reference is Europe. All our laws are being integrated into European Union framework."\par \par \uc2 It is less obvious for a country like India to look to the west. Yet one Indian board director noted that in sharing best practices on corporate governance, "Indian companies would likely find most value from American and European counterparts. Otherwise they might feel like they are contributing more than they are gaining [to other emerging markets companies]."\par \par \uc2 Another Indian director joked that sharing best practice with other companies in emerging markets, "You will find a lot of commonality in what things are not done."\par \par \uc2 Some companies in the emerging markets have appointed international directors to their boards as a way of importing best practice. Not all these board members see themselves as independent, but rather they act as advisers to the family or state owners. However, one London-based director of a Russian company told me his work on the board, "is a bit missionary - carrying things to a world where they are far away from reflecting the structures that we have."\par \par \uc2 However, looking west is not a universal approach. There are board directors and governance experts in the emerging markets who see the west as tarnished. One expert in the UAE observed that "Links to Europe and the US are not so useful after the financial crisis. They are not seen as sources of best practice anymore. It is more useful to look to Singapore and Hong Kong is Asia to look at countries that are doing a good job."\par \par \uc2 Another governance expert who advises emerging markets countries on their governance codes told me, "Many emerging markets are quite interested in what is happening in the developed world, but they are also sometimes sceptical - if they have such great governance practices and effective boards, why are all of these problems still happening?"\par \par \uc2 Clearly those that don't want to look to the US and western Europe for their best practice models have many others to choose from but no single source has emerged. Ironically, many of the countries named as alternatives - Singapore, Hong Kong and South Africa - have corporate laws and governance approaches rooted in a legacy western framework.\par \par \uc2 For now, the west is still setting the pace when it comes to corporate governance. For western business school professors and governance advisers there is a governance gold rush underway. Like many advantages enjoyed by the west, it is not clear how long this one will last. As one Indian director told me, "We will have to catch up, in one form or another. Borders get a little faded, a little lighter, and global practices do come in."\par \par \uc2 The writer is a partner at Tapestry Networks.\par \par \uc2 He can be reached at leadingview@tapestrynetworks.com\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b RE\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\