aw but adhere to a wider ethical code. Why should corporate citizens not follow a similar approach and ensure their actions comply with what is desirable in terms of the objectives and values of our society?\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 You seem to treat with equanimity the concept of major corporations breaching codes of practice agreed with government and instead engaging in what you describe as "anti-social practices". In your view it is government that is to blame for believing them in the first place. So much for Verbum meum pactum est ! On the other hand, when the government finally resorts to legislation to assert the clear original intention of parliament you wax wrathful and describe such actions as "unjust" and "anathema".\par \par \uc2 Given the clarity of those original intentions your argument on the basis of "predictable \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 " is pretty thin. It is clearly the actions of those who flaunt agreed codes and seek to undermine the intent of parliament that create unpredictability.\par \par \uc2 Paul A. Hendrick,\par \par \uc2 London N3, UK\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \