email or post to the web.   \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Since the financial crisis broke in 2008, traders have become well versed in the so-called "risk-on/risk-off" trade, jumping quickly between assets perceived as safe and those seen as risky.\par \par \uc2 Company executives, however, must feel they have been stuck in a "risk-on" world since the crisis began, with few ways of making life a little safer.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 The risks they face have always been present, but many have been magnified since the start of the crisis. They fall into three categories: financial and operational; regulatory; and reputational.\par \par \uc2 On the financial and operational side, one of the big risks is geographic: the choice between developed and emerging markets. Companies based in developed markets know that their domestic economies are stagnating and that emerging markets offer the best opportunity for growth. But turning that opportunity into a profitable venture is tough. Supermarket chains such as \uc2 Walmart\uc2  are keen to exploit the potential of China, but have struggled to turn that potential into significant profits.\par \par \uc2 Nevertheless, in the UK at least, companies that are already heavily exposed to overseas markets appear to have a greater appetite for risk than domestically focused businesses. According to a recent survey by Deloitte, the professional services company, UK-focused businesses see reducing costs and increasing cash flow as the priorities for this year. Those that are more heavily exposed to overseas markets are more likely to prioritise capital spending and new products.\par \par \uc2 "The more overseas-exposed companies are more risk loving, and they are pursuing more balance sheet expansionary strategies," says Ian Stewart, chief economist at Deloitte.\par \par \uc2 It is not just in the destination of investment that risks have become more clearly defined. Money to fund investment is also becoming more difficult to source. Raising equity through initial public offerings has become tougher since the crisis. According to the \uc2 London Stock Exchange\uc2 , there were 41 IPOs on the UK main market in 2011, a 28 per cent fall on 2010 as investors shunned new risks.\par \par \uc2 Companies that were already listed fared a little better in raising money from the stock market. Some 580 companies managed to raise money through secondary issues on the LSE in 2011, but equity investors have generally stayed risk averse. When G4S, the UK-based security company, tried to raise \u163\'00\'A32bn in a rights issue last autumn to finance an acquisition, investors balked and the deal collapsed.\par \par \uc2 Mr Stewart believes there may be a broader change in the way that companies perceive risk. "The question is whether companies are taking a 'new normal' view that involves a faltering recovery with a high level of uncertainty. That could lead to a permanently low level of risk appetite, manifesting itself in high levels of corporate cash," he says.\par \par \uc2 Regulatory and reputational risks are harder to predict than financial and operational risks but are becoming more prominent.\par \par \uc2 The clearest example of this is in the financial sector, where the crisis has prompted a new wave of regulatory effort. That ranges from the preventive, such as the new capital rules that are forcing banks to slim down their operations and hold more capital against risky business, to a renewed push on both sides of the Atlantic to pursue and punish wrongdoers. Some of the UK's largest banks last year made billions of pounds worth of provisions in their accounts to cover the costs of mis-sold payment protection insurance.\par \par \uc2 Outside the financial sector, regulators are increasingly flexing their muscles. In the European Union, for example, mobile telecoms companies are being forced to cut the amount they charge each other for connecting calls. In Australia, regulators are to introduce plain packaging for cigarettes, a move that may be followed elsewhere in the world. And in South Korea, regulators have introduced measures to protect small shopkeepers from the big supermarket chains.\par \par \uc2 More widely, however, multinationals are facing an \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  in which their impact on wider society is coming under intense scrutiny, leading to growing reputational risks.\par \par \uc2 Pressure is increasing on companies to base their decisions on more wide-ranging criteria than narrow financial metrics. The result is that many, in their public communications at least, are making much of their commitment to \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 It can be embarrassing for companies if they are found to be saying one thing but doing another. Last month it was revealed that HM Revenue & Customs had clamped down on two aggressive tax avoidance schemes run by Barclays Bank, which were designed to save \u163\'00\'A3500m. The news came just weeks after \uc2 Barclays\uc2  had released its full-year results, which were led by a section entitled "Citizenship - performance highlights".\par \par \uc2 Barclays\uc2  is not the only company to have come in for criticism because of its tax policies. \uc2 Vodafone\uc2 , the telecommunications group, and Arcadia, the retail company owned by Sir Philip Green, have also been targeted by pressure groups that want to publicise what they see as tax avoidance from both companies.\par \par \uc2 Reputational risk runs beyond the issue of tax, however. Technology company Apple, for example, has been criticised for conditions in the factories that make its products, while \uc2 Google\uc2 , the internet search engine, and \uc2 Facebook\uc2 , the social networking website, are facing concerns about the way in which they use customer data. And in the oil and gas industry, the search for new resources has pushed companies to explore in more controversial locations, from the seas around Greenland to the deep waters of the Gulf of Mexico. As BP is discovering, the price of an accident in these locations is heavy in financial and reputational terms.\par \par \uc2 As companies strive harder for growth in an uncertain global economy, the reputational risks are growing. Those that steer their way through the risks and grow at the same time will be in demand from investors and customers alike.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b RE\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 uk : \uc2 United Kingdom | eecz : \uc2 European Union Countries | eurz : \uc2 Europe | weurz : \uc2 Western Europe\cell \pa