nd redistribute by email or post to the web.   \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 When the Business in the Community charity began rolling out a new scheme to reinvigorate struggling communities last year, little did it know that the UK was about to be rocked by a terrifying wave of riots.\par \par \uc2 Last year's outbreaks of violence in cities across the country were a grim reminder of long-standing intractable socio-economic problems.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 For they came on the 30th anniversary of the 1981 riots in Toxteth and Brixton that inspired BITC's formation by business people hoping to help prevent such events in future. The organisation, which funnels financial and other support from big business to grass-roots organisations, has since grown to 850 members in the UK, representing most big private sector employers. It has also established an international following, with some 11,000 affiliates around the world.\par \par \uc2 While the latest riots have greatly disappointed and concerned members, they have also galvanised support for the Business Connector scheme, a 10-month-old BITC initiative that was originally funded with a government grant.\par \par \uc2 The project, which has exceeded expectations, arose out of BITC member research in 2010 that highlighted the need for "brokers", or individuals on the ground, to link more effectively big business with local communities. Such links are increasingly seen by members as a key part of their broader goals for \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  - a concept in its infancy at the time of the 1981 riots.\par \par \uc2 "If we don't provide the leadership and resources to help our communities, who will?" says Ken McMeikan, chief executive of Greggs, the bakery chain, and one of the business leaders that has championed the scheme.\par \par \uc2 The initiative, which was in its pilot stage when last year's riots erupted, places mainly up-and-coming middle managers in some of the most deprived parts of the UK. Initially, Connectors were placed for six months, a time frame that most found too short. As a result many second wave participants will stay for a year, and sometimes more.\par \par \uc2 Twenty individuals were chosen for the pilot phase. These ranged from two store managers from both Sainsbury's and Waitrose, the supermarket chains, to a \uc2 Royal Mail\uc2  communications manager and a high flyer on BT's graduate leadership scheme.\par \par \uc2 Early Connectors are brimming with enthusiasm. This is both in terms of what the experience will do for their careers but they also seem genuinely inspired by the possibilities for meaningful change.\par \par \uc2 "Are individuals going to return to their business better informed, a better colleague, manager, a leader more linked to the local community?" says Mark McParland, a Sainsbury's Connector who was placed in a deprived part of Brighton. "My answer is 'yes' - 1,000 times more than I would have expected."\par \par \uc2 Craig Warkman of Gregg's and another of the first Connectors (see profile below), says the beauty of the programme is that it provides a framework for companies to work successfully in communities without being prescriptive.\par \par \uc2 His employer, for example, a fast-growing chain that has become a dominant high street force in a relatively short time, has tailored its participation, in part, around making Mr Warkman its chief executive's ears on the ground. Mr Warkman, a native of north-east England, has been placed in Middlesbrough not far from Gregg's headquarters in Newcastle. He usually speaks to Mr McMeiken twice a week, for up to an hour at a time, a considerable commitment for a head of a FTSE 250 company.\par \par \uc2 Lloyds TSB\uc2 , the banking group, meanwhile, came on board in February. It has chosen to contribute \u8356\'20\'A4200,000 to fund the training and infrastructure of the scheme and will also supply up to 20 Connectors from its senior staff.\par \par \uc2 From BITC's point of view, the Connector pilot has been a significant success. It expects to have a network of more than 600 full-time Connectors over five years, working for three years in up to 200 deprived communities, says Matt Cooke, its social and investment director.\par \par \uc2 Others who are as passionate about urban regeneration as the Business Connectors, however, point to the magnitude of the task ahead.\par \par \uc2 Anna Gualtieri is a 47-year-old plugged-in university graduate who has been setting up and running businesses with her Italian husband in deprived parts of north and east London for 20 years. These include a curtain pole manufacturing business that supplies the likes of John Lewis and which operates out of a factory in Tottenham where last year's shocking riots began.\par \par \uc2 Mrs Gualtieri, one of the bigger employers in Tottenham with a staff of 50, says she has never heard of Business in the Community. This is in spite of the fact that the most high profile Connector, Kay Horne (see profile below) is based locally and has received the Prince of Wales, amongst other well-known individuals.\par \par \uc2 When her business recently put up a big sign on its factory gate saying it needed packers to box up its curtain poles, a job requiring minimal skills, no one applied.\par \par \uc2 Tottenham's most pressing problem, she says, is the uncertainty surrounding the redevelopment of the White Hart Lane football stadium. Resolving such uncertainties over big infrastructure projects by bringing together local councils, developers and other businesses is a key objective of the Connector programme.\par \par \uc2 Mrs Gualtieri says more big companies need to take a leap of faith if there are to be significant improvements in places such as Tottenham. She points to the example of Westfield, the highly successful Australian company that pioneered shopping malls globally and which last September opened one of Europe's biggest retail centres in nearby Stratford.\par \par \uc2 "There was a conscious decision to employ local people and the long-term unemployed," she says. "In the first few weeks the customer service was appalling and everyone was complaining but [the development] is now having a transformative effect."\par \par \uc2 "It just shows what big companies such as John Lewis can achieve when they send in a few smart graduates."\par \par \uc2 .......................................................................\par \par \uc2 Case study: Kay Horne of Sainsbury's\par \par \uc2 Kay Horne is the Business Connector that landed in the deep end, writes Virginia Marsh.\par \par \uc2 Ms Horne heard she would be placed in Tottenham the week after the deprived north London suburb became one of the epicentres of last year's devastating UK riots.\par \par \uc2 Ten months later the 36-year old Sainsbury's store manager has been invited to tea at Clarence House by Prince Charles, participated in one of the Queen's official Jubilee engagements and now meets Justin King, her chief executive, regularly.\par \par \uc2 "The experience has been quite surreal," says Ms Horne, a former graduate trainee from Essex, who first worked for Sainsbury's 17 years ago after leaving school.\par \par \uc2 "One minute I was worrying about putting beans on shelves and the next I was worrying about how to curtsey."\par \par \uc2 Like the other secondees to the pilot scheme, Ms Horne was not given much of a brief: it was up to her to go out into the local community and see how her organisation, and business in general, could make a difference in an area with severe socio-economic problems.\par \par \uc2 In Tottenham, this initially involved 'trudging up and down the high street' making sure local businesses knew how to access emergency funding to keep them afloat in the weeks after the riots. More recently, she has worked with The Boxing Academy, helping the Hackney-based charity - which provides alternative education to children in danger of dropping out of school - find a business mentor. She also arranged for Sainsbury's to sponsor lunches for its 20 students based in Tottenham.\par \par \uc2 Although she was already active in fund-raising and felt she understood the community around her supermarket well, the Business Connector scheme has been transformative for her.\par \par \uc2 "There is a whole underground world of charities and underground work going on out there," she says. "Previously, I was only scratching the surface. I did not realise the extent to which many community organisations need business skills rather than money."\par \par \uc2 It has also changed her career path. As a result of the visibility she has gained from her placement in Tottenham, both internally and externally, she wants to work in corporate responsibility when she returns to Sainsbury's.\par \par \uc2 .......................................................................\par \par \uc2 Case study: Craig Warkman of Greggs\par \par \uc2 Craig Warkman, a 31-year-old corporate project manager at Gregg's, the bakery chain, is the first "second generation" Business Connector, writes Virginia Marsh.\par \par \uc2 He is building on the work of a colleague, in Middlesbrough, a large Teesside town synonymous with northern England's industrial decline. As the second Gregg's secondee, he has had a more specific brief than other Connectors. Following five weeks of BITC training in London with other participants, Mr Warkman was tasked with helping transform a large vacant shopping centre into an incubation space for aspiring retailers.\par \par \uc2 He maintains that the scheme can make a significant difference because it is about motivating and training young people wherever they are in the UK.\par \par \uc2 "It is all about education. This is the only scheme of its kind here," he says.\par \par \uc2 "I really believe that a lot of [social and economic] issues can be addressed this way. There is a lot more going on in Teesside than appears."\par \par \uc2 He gives the example of one of the businesses in his regeneration scheme: a clothes designer who sells vintage clothing and also replicates it. The aspiring retailer spent six months in the incubation space that Mr Warkman helped create and has in the last month signed a lease for a shop of his own in the town centre.\par \par \uc2 Like other Connectors, he says that working closely with local government and leaders is essential.\par \par \uc2 "It was hard [working as a Connector] to begin with because we didn't have a track record. There were a lot of blockages and obstacles to getting things off the ground," he says. "Support from high profile local people was very important."\par \par \uc2 Mr Warkman says the pilot has shown the importance of making sure companies understand well a community's dynamics before sending in Connectors. To be successful, they also need to target clearly their work on a specific town or district.\par \par \uc2 Contact with other Connectors - which BITC hopes to keep alive through an alumni-style network - has helped with "quick wins". "I can pick up the phone and bounce a few ideas off the others," he says.\par \par \uc2 Keeping in touch with them in the future is "massively important", he says. "I am an expert at networking now."\par \par \uc2 .......................................................................\par \par \uc2 Case study: Will Popham of BT\par \par \uc2 For cricket fans, the Oval is a hallowed site. The south London cricket ground, home of Surrey County Cricket Club, was only the second in the sport's history to host a test match, back in 1880, and remains one of the UK's premier venues, says Virginia Marsh.\par \par \uc2 Yet when Will Popham, a Business Connector from BT, turned up in Lambeth last year he discovered that the Oval often struggled to find staff for its summer fixtures, in spite of the London borough's decades' old high rates of unemployment.\par \par \uc2 Eight months on, he has worked with the ground and the local job centre to fill 150 vacancies for stewards and other temporary ground staff, with some 100 of the jobs going to Lambeth residents.\par \par \uc2 Moreover, the new employees have had the opportunity to gain training and accreditation as ground staff and have been fast-tracked for similar work at the Olympic Games.\par \par \uc2 "There are jobs sitting out there. In this case there was a shortage of sensibly-trained stewards," says the 30-year old privately-educated Londoner who is a top graduate trainee.\par \par \uc2 "Business does a huge amount of stuff that people don't know about."\par \par \uc2 He gives the example of a \uc2 Microsoft\uc2  scheme that he has discovered provides low-cost laptops to needy individuals in places such as Lambeth.\par \par \uc2 BT selected Mr Popham as a Connector after deciding to second two trainees with Master's degrees to the pilot scheme. Mr Popham studied history at York before moving on to a post-graduate degree in business strategy and the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  at Birkbeck College, London\par \par \uc2 He says he has been surprised at how much difference such a simple scheme can make and that it has made him much more aware of the possibilities in sustainability.\par \par \uc2 "It's been a phenomenal way to connect with the frontline and understand the daily struggle," he says. "I can see how fast the pilot is acting as a catalyst. It should snowball."\par \par \uc2 BT is "thrilled" with what he and his fellow Connector have done, he adds.\par \par \uc2 Like others in the pilot, he has benefited from high level support, meeting both David Cameron and Prince Charles.\par \par \uc2 "It's not the kind of opportunity you normally get as a 30-year-old management trainee," he says. "When I get back I will be able to talk to senior, senior managers\par \par \uc2 "We are out there working with companies who want to help prevent windows getting smashed in the next lot of riots - if they happen again."\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 ccsr : \uc2 Corporate Social Responsibility | gcivds : \uc2 Civil Disruption | ccat : \uc2 Corporate/Industrial News | gcat : \uc2 Political/General News | gcns : \uc2 National Security | grisk : \uc2 Risk News | ncat : \uc2 Content Types | nfact : \uc2 Factiva Filters | nfcpex : \uc2 FC&E Executive News Filter\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx93