ost to the web.   \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Barely a day goes by without a bad business story, whether it be about greedy bonuses, tax-dodging, redundancies or companies accused of having little regard for the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  or employees. But I see a different picture, which convinces me that these headlines are a far cry from the reality in Britain.\par \par \uc2 Businesses up and down the country, be they micro-firms or large companies with hundreds of employees, are battling against the odds to grow, find new markets, and take on staff. Official figures portray an economy in double-dip recession, but business surveys paint a different picture, with many owners proceeding with a cautious optimism. That is why it is more important than ever to get behind British businesses.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 We should have pride in our companies, in the goods and services we export around the globe, and in the hard work being done in commercial parks, factories and high streets up and down the country.\par \par \uc2 If we want to be a prosperous nation in which people are happy and fulfilled, able to do the things they want to, then we need to get our head in the right place. We need to understand that wealth creation and enterprise are good. Businesses recognise that they only exist with the consent of the society in which they operate. Firms must be mindful of the way in which they behave and deal with wider society, and know they have a responsibility to behave correctly. If businesses create wealth, pay taxes and comply with the law, they are good for our nation.\par \par \uc2 Business is the UK's economic engine, creating wealth and in turn helping to provide the public services we all want, such as education, healthcare and pensions.\par \par \uc2 Business is the foundation of local communities, helping them thrive, providing hard-working people with purpose and self respect, and employment and training for those that want to learn. It's not about \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  programmes, but the contribution that businesses make every day.\par \par \uc2 Britain has the ability to recover, and our fantastic companies will help us get there. It's time to stop proclaiming economic doom and gloom and doubt. Other nations can do it and so can we. Take South Korea, for example. In the past 25 years its economy in relation to the UK has increased more than fourfold, and it grew by 3.9 per cent in 2011. That is despite its position sandwiched between the large economies of China and Japan, with few natural resources at its disposal, and no membership to a trading block, such as the European Union.\par \par \uc2 People who say Britain can't do it are talking nonsense; we just need to provide businesses with the right \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 That means providing new firms with vital access to capital. It also means investment in infrastructure, digital, rail and aviation; networks that allow businesses to move around and communicate, that make Britain an attractive and competitive place to do business.\par \par \uc2 It also means reducing the burden of regulation that comes not only from our government, but Brussels. We need a planning system that does not restrict expansion plans, or weigh down firms with reams of paperwork, and more incentives for firms to invest in new technology, and take on staff. Business also needs an education system that provides school leavers with the skills they need and makes them ready, able and willing to enter the workplace.\par \par \uc2 Without a truly enterprise-friendly \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 , we can't expect to see businesses thrive and grow and it is ultimately down to the government to deliver. Sticking to plan A and reducing the deficit is important, but so too is fostering growth. Repeated promises to put growth at the heart of all policy making by ministers are in danger of being broken. Politicians across all parties have failed to deliver a reality that matches the growth rhetoric. We need an enterprise-friendly government that truly understands how to help business to grow with a common goal in mind.\par \par \uc2 We have great businesses in Britain, now is the time to make Britain great.\par \par \uc2 John Longworth is director-general of the British Chambers of Commerce\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b RE\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 uk : \uc2 United Kingdom | eecz : \uc2 European Union Countries | eurz : \uc2 Europe | weurz : \uc2 Western Europe\cell \pard \ql