0 \uc2 English\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CY\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 (Copyright (c) 2012, Dow Jones & Company, Inc.) \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 VIENNA -- While Europeans worry about the potentially negative environmental aspects of exploiting shale gas, \uc2 Gerhard Roiss\uc2 , chief executive of Austrian oil and gas company \uc2 OMV AG\uc2 , has a simple message: Shale gas is a necessary part of a sustainable European energy mix.\par \par \uc2 Not to embrace shale gas risks the future competitiveness of European industry, he says.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 European Union\uc2  agencies "should start this communication campaign to show the impact for Europe if we don't go into shale gas."\par \par \uc2 Without such a move, he says, energy-intensive industries, such as the petrochemical industry, may soon begin to leave Europe for the U.S. because of the abundance of cheap energy there.\par \par \uc2 "Nowadays the price for gas in the U.S. is one-third or a quarter compared with [prices in] Europe. Industry is asking, 'where do I invest tomorrow?'\par \par \uc2 "This is a big impact and it's happening now," he says, adding that "this isn't seen by the people here who are opposed to it [shale gas exploration]."\par \par \uc2 "This isn't seen today. But when it is, it will be too late."\par \par \uc2 The irony, Mr. Roiss says, is that, while exploitation of shale gas using hydraulic fracturing, or "fracking", is widely opposed in Europe, an energy shortage has resulted in the importation of coal -- a much more polluting fossil fuel -- from the U.S.\par \par \uc2 "When it comes to shale gas, there's a huge campaign against it. When it comes to coal, which has twice the CO2 emissions, you don't hear about it," he says, adding with a laugh, "there must be a strong lobby for coal in Europe."\par \par \uc2 Burning more coal for energy is an environmentally retrograde step, he says. Part of the problem is that politicians put short-term popularity from backing popular campaigns ahead of working out a long-term energy policy. "We now import coal because politicians aren't able to handle the shale gas issue," Mr. Roiss says.\par \par \uc2 His criticism of politicians comes from the unusual standpoint, for the CEO of an Austrian company partially owned by the state, of political independence. He is the first CEO at OMV not to be a member of a political party, rare in a country that prides itself on its "proporz" [proportional representation] system to fill semi-public and public jobs, ensuring that members of the two main political parties evenly split positions in the country.\par \par \uc2 To those who think that keeping shale gas exploitation out of Europe is environmentally sensible, Mr. Roiss has a stark rejoinder: "We need shale gas because today's situation is worse," he says, referring to the coal imports.\par \par \uc2 The U.S. shale-gas boom is helping to reshape the world's energy structure and has the potential to replace coal in electricity generation. U.S. shale-gas production increased from 425 million cubic meters a day in 2010 to 700 million cubic meters a day this year, according to the \uc2 Organization of the Petroleum Exporting Countries\uc2 ' 2012 World Oil Outlook. The \uc2 International Energy Agency\uc2  has called the impact of shale-gas energy in the U.S. "profound," adding that the resource would help make the U.S. energy self-sufficient in net terms by 2035. Currently, it imports about 20% of its primary energy needs, the IEA says.\par \par \uc2 The situation in Europe could hardly be more of a contrast. In the EU, regulatory jurisdiction is at the level of the 27 national member states. Among these, France and Bulgaria have banned fracking altogether, while other countries have raised environmental bars so high as to prohibit development.\par \par \uc2 This is effectively what happened in Mr. Roiss's back yard, when OMV sought to conduct experimental fracking in a region in Austria known as the Weinviertel, or wine region, after its expanses of vineyards.\par \par \uc2 The energy giant came up against hefty regional opposition. Locals opposed the idea, worried about the effects on both the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  and the area's economy, which is based around farming, with a growing eco-tourism sector.\par \par \uc2 "Even if it were proven that the drilling had no effect on the wine, who wants to buy wine out of a gas field?" says Sabine Randl, a member of the grass roots opposition group Weinviertel statt Gasviertel, or "Wine Region instead of Gas Region."\par \par \uc2 Environmentalists are concerned about not only the use of chemicals in the fracking process and their possible effect on ground water, but are also concerned about the amount of water needed. There have also been concerns about fracking triggering earth tremors and contamination of areas around the drilling sites.\par \par \uc2 Opposition to fracking in the Weinviertel became so strong that politicians pushed through a bill in parliament to now require an extensive environmental impact study before giving a new fracking project the go ahead. Before the bill such studies weren't always required.\par \par \uc2 "These studies are very strict, which means that fracking won't happen, at least not in Lower Austria [where the region is located]," said Irmgard Poschacher, a spokeswoman for the Ministry of \b \highlight22\uc2 Environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 . OMV decided to bow to pressure and canceled plans to carry out the test drilling.\par \par \uc2 Currently, therefore, while fracking is -- at least on paper -- allowed in Austria, the costs and difficulties in obtaining the relevant permissions make it impossible in practical terms.\par \par \uc2 An irony of the Weinviertel story is that OMV had wanted to drill in the area to test a new form of "clean fracking," which, unlike conventional fracking with its chemical additives, would use little or no chemicals.\par \par \uc2 For Mr. Roiss drilling in Austria is now a closed topic.\par \par \uc2 He points to the widely differing and stricter environmental standards among European countries compared with the unified regulatory system in the U.S. What is needed, Mr. Roiss says, is the creation of a Europe-wide policy and industry standards, something that the EU could put in place. Europe, he says, needs to pool know-how, and use test markets, perhaps in Poland or the U.K. -- EU countries where fracking is already taking place -- to develop European standards that would allow companies to pursue not only commercially viable projects, but also environmentally responsible ones.\par \par \uc2 At the moment, he says, people aren't even allowing companies to develop methods to prove fracking can be done in an environmentally responsible way.\par \par \uc2 Mr. Roiss says he is in discussions with the \uc2 European Commission\uc2 , the EU's executive arm, to create a European strategy. This may well be a long slog, but Mr. Roiss, an avid marathon runner in his spare time, is undeterred.\par \par \uc2 For now, OMV, which in 2011 saw sales of <euro>34 billion ($43.3 billion) and employs almost 30,000 people, is concentrating on exploring and developing new gas supplies in the areas close to its main markets in Europe and Turkey. In February, the company announced a potentially large gas discovery in the Black Sea, where it is conducting seismic studies which Mr. Roiss hopes will someday mean a new source of gas for Europe.\par \par \uc2 "Shale gas is important, but we have also the issue of Nabucco [a proposed pipeline to bring gas from the Caspian Sea region to Europe in which OMV has a stake], the issue of TANAP [the Trans Anatolian Natural Gas Pipeline Project which will bring Caspian Sea gas to Turkey's western border], the issue of Azeri gas, Iraqi gas, the North Sea, the Black Sea."\par \par \uc2 Away from arguments over shale-gas fracking or the geopolitics of gas exploration and development, Mr. Roiss is an enthusiastic supporter of \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 . When talking, for example, about the possibilities for gas's ability to improve the standard of living in places such as Northern Iraq, his face lights up.\par \par \uc2 "My strong opinion is that, as managers of big companies, we have to be aware that we have a responsibility, a growing responsibility besides our direct business, besides our balance sheet," he says. In the future, society will have to rely increasingly on cooperation between businesses and government to fulfill social needs, he says, especially in areas such as reducing youth unemployment.\par \par \uc2 To give an example, he describes a project in Pakistan where OMV is running schools for 3,000 children and points to his speech at last year's OPEC conference where he said oil and gas companies needed to care more about youth employment in the regions where they did business.\par \par \uc2 In a traditionally hard-edged business, Mr. Roiss's social concern has won him approval in some unlikely places. Even anti-fracking activist Ms. Randl admits to being an admirer.\par \par {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.djreprints.com/link/DJRFactiva.html?FACTIVA=weco20121119000022"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 License this article from Dow Jones Reprint Service}}}\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CO\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 oemv : \uc2 OMV AG\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b IN\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 i1 : \uc2 Energy | i13 : \uc2 Crude Oil/Natural Gas | i14 : \uc2 Petroleum/Coal Products\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr