bilities in this \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Writers and editors at The \uc2 New York Times\uc2  interviewed leaders and chief executives from Wall Street to Silicon Valley in a day-long conference at the Times Center in New York. Whether you attending in person or watched our video feed above, you can continue the conversation on \uc2 Twitter\uc2  with the hash tag {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://twitter.com/search?q=%23DBConf&src=hash"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 #DBconf}}}\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 The official conference web site included biographies of the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://nytdealbookconference.com/speakers.php"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 speakers}}}\uc2  and an {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://nytdealbookconference.com/agenda.php"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 agenda}}}\uc2  for the day\u8217\'20\'19s events.\par \par \uc2 5:30 P.M. | The Justin Bieber of Economics\par \par \uc2 An audience member says that seeing Mr. Krugman is like being a 13-year-old at a Justin Bieber concert.\par \par \uc2 But the economist, who is a fan of the band Arcade Fire, admits he has never actually listened to Mr. Bieber\u8217\'20\'19s music.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CIt\u8217\'20\'19s taken some work, but I\u8217\'20\'19ve never heard him.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 He says, however, that he has measured himself against the young pop star in other ways. Mr. Krugman says he has about 1/40th of Mr. Bieber\u8217\'20\'19s followers on \uc2 Twitter\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 @{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://twitter.com/kevinroose"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 kevinroose}}}\uc2  But @{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://twitter.com/nytimeskrugman"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 nytimeskrugman}}}\uc2  has heard Arcade Fire. So a net gain. {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://twitter.com/search/%23DBConf"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 #DBConf}}}\par \par \uc2 \u8212\'20\'14 NYTFridge (@NYTFridge) {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://twitter.com/NYTFridge/status/278988469949329408"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 December 12, 2012}}}\par \par \uc2 But he *has* heard of stochastic calculus! RT @{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://twitter.com/kevinroose"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 kevinroose}}}\uc2 : The big takeaway from {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://twitter.com/search/%23dbconf"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 #dbconf}}}\uc2 : \uc2 Paul Krugman\uc2  has never heard Justin Bieber.\par \par \uc2 \u8212\'20\'14 Nick Confessore (@nickconfessore) {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://twitter.com/nickconfessore/status/278988187311935488"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 December 12, 2012}}}\par \par \uc2 That\u8217\'20\'19s all for the inaugural DealBook conference. A reception at the Times Center follows the conference, but the conversation continues online at {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://twitter.com/search?q=%23DBConf&src=hash"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 #DBConf}}}\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 \u8212\'20\'14 William Alden\par \par \uc2 5:25 P.M. | On the Treasury and the Fed\par \par \uc2 Mr. Krugman is asked what he would do if asked to be Treasury secretary or Federal Reserve chairman.\par \par \uc2 In either case, he says, he would ask, \u8220\'20\'1CAre you sure about this?\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 On a more serious note, he outlines some criticism of the current Treasury secretary, \uc2 Timothy F. Geithner\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CI certainly hope that whoever is the next Treasury secretary is going to be more confrontational when necessary than Geithner\u8217\'20\'19s been,\u8221\'20\'1D Mr. Krugman says. \u8220\'20\'1CHe\u8217\'20\'19s been way too willing to let the banks put on debt relief for homeowners, was apparently instrumental in Obama\u8217\'20\'19s very soft line that last time we hit the debt ceiling.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 He also spoke about \uc2 Ben Bernanke\uc2 , the Fed chairman.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CWhat I really want is \uc2 Ben Bernanke\uc2  of 2000 who was much more aggressive in the use of monetary policy than Ben Bernakke of recent years has been. Although, he seems to be gaining.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CI think we\u8217\'20\'19re starting to see the \uc2 Ben Bernanke\uc2  who hired me at Princeton starting to make an appearance.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 \u8212\'20\'14 William Alden\par \par \uc2 5:12 P.M. | Approaching the Cliff\par \par \uc2 On trading floors and in board rooms, everyone is talking about the so-called fiscal cliff. Mr. Krugman speculates the odds of going over the cliff are even. That would trigger spending cuts and tax increases early next year.\par \par \uc2 But Mr. Krugman is an economist, not a Washington insider. He says the economy could be harmed even if a deal is reached in time. \u8220\'20\'1CThe most damaging parts of the fiscal cliff are not even on the table,\u8221\'20\'1D he says.\par \par \uc2 In any case, the forecast is gloomy.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CI\u8217\'20\'19m worried,\u8221\'20\'1D Mr. Krugman says. \u8220\'20\'1CI\u8217\'20\'19m even more worried about the stuff that\u8217\'20\'19s just a couple of months further down the road, which is the debt ceiling. Those are scary things.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 He notes that this economic threat is a political creation \u8212\'20\'14 a situation that\u8217\'20\'19s become all too common these days.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CObama has to put a stop to this,\u8221\'20\'1D Mr. Krugman says. \u8220\'20\'1CHe has to draw a line. When better to do that than right at the beginning of his second term?\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 \u8212\'20\'14 William Alden\par \par \uc2 4:52 P.M. | The Rise of China\par \par \uc2 How will growth in China affect the United States? Mr. Krugman is wary.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CI would say that to some extent we are hurt by Chinese growth, not because of the competition of Chinese products in our market,\u8221\'20\'1D he says. \u8220\'20\'1CBut because there are scarce natural resources.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 He continues: \u8220\'20\'1CIf you worry about climate change, China\u8217\'20\'19s growth is a wonderful human success story that could kill us all.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 But he offers a caveat.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CAll economic statistics are just a boring form of science fiction, but China is more fictional than most.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 \u8212\'20\'14 William Alden\par \par \uc2 4:40 P.M. | Krugman\u8217\'20\'19s View From Washington\par \par {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://topics.nytimes.com/top/opinion/editorialsandoped/oped/columnists/paulkrugman/index.html"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Paul Krugman}}}\uc2 , an Op-Ed columnist for The \uc2 New York Times\uc2 , is talking with {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/people/l/david_leonhardt/index.html"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 David Leonhardt}}}\uc2 , Washington bureau chief for The Times.\par \par \uc2 \u8212\'20\'14 Eric Owles\par \par \uc2 4:30 P.M. | No Easy Fix Is Seen for Europe\par \par \uc2 Fixing Europe will not be easy or fast, according to the panel\u8217\'20\'19s members. Mr. Clementi says that he isn\u8217\'20\'19t expecting the demise of a European nation or a \u8220\'20\'1Ccatastrophe\u8221\'20\'1D anytime soon, but he thinks that an Italy or a France or a Spain will suffer from what he calls a depression.\par \par \uc2 Mr. Lasry argues that Europe still has an enormous number of problems, which haven\u8217\'20\'19t been fully accounted for. He notes that the cost of buying a European company remains on average more than nine times earnings.\par \par \uc2 And yet, he says that there\u8217\'20\'19s still a reason to put money into European economies. \u8220\'20\'1CAs long as I know that France is going to be around next year,\u8221\'20\'1D he says, \u8220\'20\'1CI\u8217\'20\'19m happy to invest in France.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Ultimately, while Europe may not collapse, Mr. Lasry, the continent may be home to a \u8220\'20\'1Clost generation\u8221\'20\'1D that hasn\u8217\'20\'19t enjoyed the growth of its predecessors.\par \par \uc2 Mr. Veron says that there isn\u8217\'20\'19t any just one problem that needs fixing. But perhaps the most intractable may be a very fundamental one: a breaking of trust. Investors aren\u8217\'20\'19t likely to see Italian debt or Spanish debt as risk-free anymore.\par \par \uc2 That will require creating a new kind of asset that can draw the faith of investors, he says, describing what essentially sounds like a European-wide bond. \u8220\'20\'1CWe need something that is issued at the European level to have this level of trust among investors,\u8221\'20\'1D he says.\par \par \uc2 \u8212\'20\'14 Michael J. de la Merced\par \par \uc2 4:23 P.M. | \uc2 Eric Schmidt\uc2 : How We Outrace the Robots\par \par \uc2 Off the stage, Mr. Hardy asked the executive chairman of Google where in the world the jobs for a great many people will be. His advice: We have to learn how to \u8220\'20\'1Coutrace the robots.\u8221\'20\'1D {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://bits.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/12/12/eric-schmidt-how-we-outrace-the-robots/"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Read more \u187\'00\'BB}}}\par \par \uc2 4:05 P.M. | What\u8217\'20\'19s Next in the Euro Crisis?\par \par \uc2 Gian Luca Clementi, an associate professor of economics at New York University\u8217\'20\'19s Stern School of Business; Marc Lasry, chief executive of Avenue Capital; and Nicolas Veron, a senior fellow at Bruegel, a research firm in Brussels; are talking about the European debt crisis. The conversation is being moderated by Larry Ingrassia, the business editor for The New York Times.\par \par \uc2 Mr. Lasry\u8217\'20\'19s hedge fund is {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.nytimes.com/2012/07/23/business/avenue-capital-hedge-fund-takes-chance-on-euro-zone.html"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 betting on a long-term come back for Europe}}}\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 On the Agenda: A steady stream of plans and summits has so far managed to stave off disaster in the eurozone, but deep structural problems persist. Is one of the world\u8217\'20\'19s major economic regions fated to stumble on through crisis, or is there a prospect of resolution?\par \par \uc2 \u8212\'20\'14 Eric Owles\par \par \uc2 3:46 P.M. | Market Mover\par \par {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/people/d/charles_duhigg/index.html"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Mr. Duhigg}}}\uc2  is discussing his book, \u8220\'20\'1CThe Power of Habit: Why We Do What We Do in Life and Business.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Here is an excerpt from {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.nytimes.com/2012/03/11/books/review/the-power-of-habit-by-charles-duhigg.html"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 The Times Sunday book review}}}\uc2 :\par \par \uc2 He makes his case by presenting fascinating stories and case histories. Readers will learn how and why Target can tell which of its female customers are pregnant, even before they have told their friends and family; how Rick Warren went from a depressed minister of a small congregation to the leader of one of the biggest megachurches in the world; why Rosa Parks\u8217\'20\'19s refusal to give up her seat started a movement when similar refusals by others had not; and why a 1987 fire in a \uc2 London Underground\uc2  station failed to be contained, leading to the deaths of 31 people.\par \par \uc2 \u8212\'20\'14 Eric Owles\par \par \uc2 3:19 P.M. | Coffee!\par \par \uc2 We\u8217\'20\'19re breaking for coffee, but we\u8217\'20\'19ll back at 3:45 with Charles Duhigg, a reporter for The \uc2 New York Times\uc2 , and the author of \u8220\'20\'1CThe Power of Habit\u8221\'20\'1D. Submit you questions and comments for the panel at #DBConf.\par \par \uc2 \u8212\'20\'14 Eric Owles\par \par \uc2 3:19 P.M. | On \b \highlight22\uc2 Corporate Social Responsibility\b0 \highlight\par \par \uc2 Ms. Nooyi says she doesn\u8217\'20\'19t see \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  as something separate from the business model. Rather, she says, it should be woven in.\par \par \uc2 For instance, she says, using less plastic and less water is good for the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  and it helps \uc2 PepsiCo\uc2  reduce its costs. On diversity, she says she has fostered an \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  that is more welcoming for women \u8212\'20\'14 something that, she says, strengthens the company.\par \par \uc2 Ms. Nooyi says all of this is intended to \u8220\'20\'1Csustain a level of performance into the future, rather than just the duration of the C.E.O.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 \u8212\'20\'14 Wiliam Alden\par \par \uc2 3:09 P.M. | \uc2 PepsiCo\uc2 \u8217\'20\'19s Chief on the Soda Ban\par \par \uc2 Add Ms. Nooyi to the list of people unhappy with Michael R. Bloomberg\u8217\'20\'19s ban on the sale of large sugary drinks.\par \par \uc2 She said she wished the mayor had solicited more input from the private sector, and said there were more subtle ways he could have gone about encouraging New Yorkers to be healthier.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CThere are so many behavioral methods we could have tried, rather than an uneven, heavy-handed way of saying 16 ounces is bad,\u8221\'20\'1D she said.\par \par \uc2 \u8212\'20\'14 William Alden\par \par \uc2 3:00 P.M. | The Insider Trading Question\par \par \uc2 Mr. Stewart delves into a topic that he\u8217\'20\'19s very familiar with: insider trading. With the investigations that the federal government is prosecuting in recent years, how concerned are the panelists with that crime?\par \par \uc2 Mr. Dalio, who doesn\u8217\'20\'19t seem to regard it as a problem within his firm, says that the biggest danger is to treat hedge funds as a group or alternatives as a group. Let\u8217\'20\'19s not tar everyone with the same brush, he warns.\par \par \uc2 Mr. Rubenstein takes a similar tack. \u8220\'20\'1CNo investor really says to me, \u8216\'20\'18I\u8217\'20\'19m really worried about insider trading within your organization,\u8217\'20\'19\u8221\'20\'1D he says. At the same time, Carlyle spends a lot of time and money on compliance because it\u8217\'20\'19s trying to scare employees and letting them know that the crime won\u8217\'20\'19t be tolerated.\par \par \uc2 But Mr. Schwarzman has a different, and much more personal, point of view. He notes his own close brush with insider trading this way: \u8220\'20\'1CI was privileged to have an office next to a guy named Dennis Levine.\u8221\'20\'1D Amid chuckles from the audience, Mr. Schwarzman continues that Mr. Levine, his former colleague at \uc2 Lehman Brothers\uc2 , was stealing his deals.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CI must tell you, it\u8217\'20\'19s the most traumatizing thing that\u8217\'20\'19s happened in my business career,\u8221\'20\'1D the \uc2 Blackstone\uc2  chief says.\u8221\'20\'1DWhen we started \uc2 Blackstone\uc2 , I vowed that would never happen. And it has not.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 He recalls his speech to the first batch of business school recruits that his firm hired, replete with the line, \u8220\'20\'1CIf you ever violate that, I will hunt you down and send you to jail.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 It\u8217\'20\'19s a speech that didn\u8217\'20\'19t go well with Mr. Schwarzman\u8217\'20\'19s other partners as the right kind of introduction, he says. \u8220\'20\'1CBut I didn\u8217\'20\'19t care.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 He still gives the speech he says. But it may have lost some of its impact: \u8220\'20\'1COf course, someone else warns them.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 \u8212\'20\'14 Michael J. de la Merced\par \par \uc2 2:51 P.M. | The C.E.O Interview\par \par {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.nytimes.com/2012/07/09/business/pepsico-with-muller-by-quaker-yogurt-aims-at-a-surging-market.html"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Indra Nooyi, the chief of PepsiCo}}}\uc2 , is talking with {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://topics.nytimes.com/top/opinion/editorialsandoped/oped/columnists/joenocera/index.html"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Joe Nocera}}}\uc2 , an Op-Ed columnist for The \uc2 New York Times\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Earlier this year, Ms. Nooyi was discussed as a candidate to become the next head of the \uc2 World Bank\uc2 , but recent shake-ups at \uc2 PepsiCo\uc2  have led people to believe that she will remain with the company for the foreseeable future.\par \par \uc2 On the Agenda: The last few years have seen unprecedented turbulence in the global economy. How does a global corporation navigate through such times?\par \par \uc2 \u8212\'20\'14 Eric Owles\par \par \uc2 2:36 P.M. | Where Do These Investors Want to Be?\par \par \uc2 Mr. Dalio says that within his firm, there\u8217\'20\'19s a constant discussion about tactics, and where to be, and where not to be. \u8220\'20\'1CIt\u8217\'20\'19s hard to have a portfolio without bias, and have a very well-balanced portfolio,\u8221\'20\'1D he says, with too many people having a bias toward being long.\par \par \uc2 That said, here\u8217\'20\'19s what he thinks:\par \par \uc2 * There\u8217\'20\'19s a place for gold.\par \par \uc2 * Equities will probably do better than bonds longer term\par \par \uc2 * Emerging markets will do well, with the squeeze on their currencies largely over.\par \par \uc2 Mr. Schwarzman said that \uc2 Blackstone\uc2 \u8217\'20\'19s moving out of junk bonds and into high-yielding bank debt because the latter carries a floating interest rate instead of a fixed on.\par \par \uc2 Mr. Rubenstein had a much more prosaic answer: He doesn\u8217\'20\'19t want to be buying apartments in new York City above the 60th floor. \u8220\'20\'1CIt\u8217\'20\'19s a bubble,\u8221\'20\'1D he says. His investment companions on stage quickly chime in that neither of them is a member of that group either.\par \par \uc2 \u8212\'20\'14 Michael J. de la Merced\par \par \uc2 2:30 P.M. | Where to Invest? Where to Avoid?\par \par \uc2 Mr. Stewart asks the panelists where are the great places to invest, given that times of turmoil can yield attractive opportunities if one has conviction.\par \par \uc2 For Mr. Dalio, the world is in a great period of deleveraging. But he thinks that risk premiums could stand to be squeezed a bit more. At the same time, any expansion of risk premiums will generally be a negative development for asset classes as a whole.\par \par \uc2 At some point, however, Mr. Dalio said that betting against corporate bonds will prove to be highly attractive. That time hasn\u8217\'20\'19t come yet, he said.\par \par \uc2 Mr. Rubenstein, who is an optimist that the fiscal cliff will be resolved \u8212\'20\'14 though not necessarily in a pretty way \u8212\'20\'14 thinks that the United States is still the most attractive place to strike private equity deals. For instance, the health care industry could prove attractive, as the Obama administration\u8217\'20\'19s regulatory changes take effect and the American populace continues aging.\par \par \uc2 But the Carlyle chief added that some geographically unusual parts of the world could also yield interesting opportunities. One such place is sub-Saharan Africa, which he predicts could eventually have more available workers than in China.\par \par \uc2 Mr. Schwarzman said that any resolution of the fiscal cliff is likely to create some drag on the economy. \u8220\'20\'1CWe\u8217\'20\'19re not optimists on the runaway upside scale,\u8221\'20\'1D he said.\par \par \uc2 That said, the \uc2 Blackstone\uc2  cofounder lauded the promise of real estate, an asset class that comprises an enormous part of his firm\u8217\'20\'19s business. The firm has been busy buying up assets like warehouses in Europe, earning a healthy return \u8220\'20\'1Cwithout doing anything.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Where are places to avoid, Mr. Stewart asks?\par \par \uc2 Mr. Rubenstein identifies one place as Russia. \u8220\'20\'1CRussia might be attractive to visit as a tourist, and it may have great natural resources,\u8221\'20\'1D he said. But it\u8217\'20\'19s hard to make money there in private equity.\par \par \uc2 Mr. Schwarzman said anther place was India, citing a difficult business governance structure that has long bedeviled outside investors. \u8220\'20\'1CEven some Indians are giving up on India,\u8221\'20\'1D he said.\par \par \uc2 \u8212\'20\'14 Michael J. de la Merced\par \par \uc2 2:01 P.M. | Follow the Money in \uc2 Private Equity\uc2  and Hedge Funds\par \par {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://dealbook.nytimes.com/2012/03/29/large-hedge-funds-fared-well-in-2011/"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Ray Dalio, the founder of Bridgewater Associates}}}\uc2 ; {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://dealbook.nytimes.com/2012/11/08/carlyle-swings-to-profit-as-holdings-value-rises/"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 David Rubenstein, a co-founder of The Carlyle Group}}}\uc2 ; and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.nytimes.com/2012/12/09/business/financiers-bet-on-rental-housing.html"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Stephen A. Schwarzman, chief of The Blackstone Group}}}\uc2 ; discuss what they are focusing on next in a conversation moderated by {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://topics.nytimes.com/topics/reference/timestopics/people/s/james_b_stewart/index.html"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 James B. Stewart}}}\uc2 , a columnist for The \uc2 New York Times\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Now that many private equity firms have become public companies, they are under pressure to provide more reliable returns.\par \par \uc2 DealBook\u8217\'20\'19s Peter Lattman examined some of the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://dealbook.nytimes.com/2012/12/11/private-equity-firms-now-have-very-public-profiles/"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 problems facing private equity firms}}}\uc2  today: a potential tax increase, fundraising slowdowns and the aftermath of the buyout boom.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CThese firms that were once castigated for being brash \u8216\'20\'18Barbarians at the Gate\u8217\'20\'19 are now staid asset managers selling a variety of financial products and services,\u8221\'20\'1D said \uc2 Kelly DePonte\uc2 , a managing director at \uc2 Probitas Partners\uc2 , a company that raises money for private equity firms.\par \par \uc2 On the Agenda: How are major forces in private equity and hedge funds shifting their focus? Can we get a good sense of where opportunity lies around the globe?\par \par \uc2 \u8212\'20\'14 Eric Owles\par \par \uc2 12:47 P.M. | Lunch!\par \par \uc2 We\u8217\'20\'19re breaking for lunch, but we\u8217\'20\'19ll be back at 2 p.m. with \uc2 Ray Dalio\uc2  of Bridgewater Associates, \uc2 David Rubenstein\uc2  of the \uc2 Carlyle Group\uc2  and \uc2 Stephen A. Schwarzman\uc2  of the \uc2 Blackstone Group\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 \u8212\'20\'14 Eric Owles\par \par \uc2 12:39 P.M. | Preparing for an I.P.O.?\par \par \uc2 Mr. Hardy asks about \uc2 Twitter\uc2 \u8217\'20\'19s plans for an initial public offering, but Mr. Costolo holds his cards close to the vest. He echoes a sentiment often heard in Silicon Valley, that an I.P.O. isn\u8217\'20\'19t what the company is focused on.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CI think of a public offering as a financing event for the company,\u8221\'20\'1D he says.\par \par \uc2 \u8212\'20\'14 William Alden\par \par \uc2 12:34 P.M. | Advertising on \uc2 Twitter\par \par \uc2 Companies are still figuring out what it means to advertise on social media. Mr. Costolo gives an example. Tide, he says, seized an opportunity to build an advertising campaign around a viral photograph featuring the product, using a caption contest.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CThey completely flipped upside down the way you would normally think about advertising: from, \u8216\'20\'18Let\u8217\'20\'19s do a 30-second spot and create buzz around it,\u8217\'20\'19 to, \u8216\'20\'18Let\u8217\'20\'19s take the buzz and generate a 30-second spot around it,\u8217\'20\'19\u8221\'20\'1D he says.\par \par \uc2 \u8212\'20\'14 William Alden\par \par \uc2 12:28 P.M. | What Is \uc2 Twitter\uc2 , Anyway?\par \par \uc2 Mr. Costolo describes \uc2 Twitter\uc2  is a global town square.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CIn Ancient Greece you had the agora,\u8221\'20\'1D Mr. Costolo says. \u8220\'20\'1CThe news was exchanged and unfiltered by the participants in the news.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 He adds: \u8220\'20\'1CThese new technologies and disruptions are all about reducing the friction in time and space in getting the information out. But in reducing the friction in time and space, you lose the perspective.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 \u8212\'20\'14 William Alden\par \par \uc2 12:20 P.M. | \uc2 Twitter\uc2 \u8217\'20\'19s Chief Talks \uc2 Twitter\par \par {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9503E4DF1431F933A05754C0A9649D8B63"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Dick Costolo}}}\uc2 , the chief of \uc2 Twitter\uc2 , is talking with Mr. Hardy.\par \par \uc2 \u8212\'20\'14 Eric Owles\par \par \uc2 12:02 P.M. | On Education and Women\par \par \uc2 Much of the innovation panel comes back to education. Mr. Moritz says the country\u8217\'20\'19s immigration policies are holding back development. \u8220\'20\'1CEvery foreign-born student who comes to the United States to study would pursue a Ph.D. if given the opportunity,\u8221\'20\'1D he says.\par \par \uc2 And the panelists also note that there has been a problem with drawing in other groups, like women, into math and the sciences, holding back some innovation. Mr. Moritz bemoans the historical discrimination that discouraged women from pursuing these increasingly important subject areas.\par \par \uc2 Ms. Shih remembers how there were relatively few women in her computer science classes at \uc2 Stanford University\uc2 , something that has since begun to change.\par \par \uc2 \u8212\'20\'14 Michael J. de la Merced\par \par \uc2 11:44 A.M. | \uc2 Google\uc2 \u8217\'20\'19s Chief on Disruptive Innovation\par \par \uc2 Mr. Schmidt spends a lot of time these days thinking about innovation. And Silicon Valley has continued to be a font of disruptive change.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CTechnology platforms are so pervasive that they literally upend their predecessors,\u8221\'20\'1D he says.\par \par \uc2 It\u8217\'20\'19s a rate of change that is really fast, but Mr. Schmidt says one potential brake is the patent wars, in which \uc2 Google\uc2  is \u8212\'20\'14 he says \u8212\'20\'14 a reluctant participant. Patents can be important for smaller inventors, but in the hands of big corporations they become huge weapons. That can stymie nascent breakthroughs.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CIf there\u8217\'20\'19s a person in this room who comes up with a brilliant new phone,\u8221\'20\'1D he says, \u8220\'20\'1Cwhere are you going to get the patents from? There are over 200,000 of them.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Another possible problem, Mr. Schmidt says, is that the United States is falling behind. He cites a recently published survey showing the country falling behind the likes of Singapore.\par \par \uc2 We have all these great sports rivalries in the United States, he says. \u8220\'20\'1CHere\u8217\'20\'19s the most important rivalry that we have, and we\u8217\'20\'19re not upset about it?\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 The government is taking up the fight somewhat effectively, Mr. Schmidt asks, pointing to initiatives like the Education Department\u8217\'20\'19s Race to the Top. There is one issue, however. \u8220\'20\'1CAs it turns out,\u8221\'20\'1D he says, \u8220\'20\'1Cin government you can\u8217\'20\'19t have any losers.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 \u8212\'20\'14 Michael J. de la Merced\par \par \uc2 11:29 A.M. | Goldman\u8217\'20\'19s Next Leader\par \par \uc2 Mr. Sorkin asks Mr. Blankfein if he has had enough of being chief executive. \u8220\'20\'1COh, I\u8217\'20\'19ve had enough,\u8221\'20\'1D Mr. Blankfein says. \u8220\'20\'1CDoes that answer your question?\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CI come in every day and I\u8217\'20\'19m happy to be with the people I work with and it\u8217\'20\'19s exciting,\u8221\'20\'1D he says. \u8220\'20\'1CWould I like it better if I were at home watching you on TV every day? I don\u8217\'20\'19t think I\u8217\'20\'19d like it that much.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Concerning the bank\u8217\'20\'19s next chief, he says: \u8220\'20\'1CI think it\u8217\'20\'19s a very high likelihood, close to 100 percent, that the next leader of \uc2 Goldman Sachs\uc2  is at \uc2 Goldman Sachs\uc2 .\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 \u8212\'20\'14 William Alden\par \par \uc2 11:27 A.M. | \uc2 Google\uc2 \u8217\'20\'19s Chief on the Search for Innovation\par \par {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.nytimes.com/2012/07/16/world/europe/16iht-educside16.html"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Michael Moritz}}}\uc2 , the chairman of Sequoia Capital, \uc2 Eric Schmidt\uc2 , the chairman of Google, and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.nytimes.com/2009/11/12/business/smallbusiness/12guide.html"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Clara Shih}}}\uc2 , the chief executive of Hearsay Social, are discussing technology\u8217\'20\'19s economic impact with \uc2 Quentin Hardy\uc2 , deputy technology editor of The New York Times.\par \par \uc2 Google\uc2  shares fell sharply in October after the company released a {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.nytimes.com/2012/10/19/technology/google-shares-drop-after-earnings-disappoint.html"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 disappointing earnings report}}}\uc2  that reflected the challenges of mobile devices.\par \par \uc2 On the Agenda: Financial innovation in the last decade became a discredited notion, responsible for increased and misunderstood systemic risks. But in other sectors of the economy, notably technology, there is a thriving innovation economy, providing real impetus for economic growth and change.\par \par \uc2 11:19 A.M. | Goldman and the News\par \par \uc2 Mr. Sorkin asks Mr. Blankfein if he reads the newspaper these days, noting that in the past the Goldman chief has said his wife reads the paper for him.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CIn some industries, they have their wife go out and start the car for them,\u8221\'20\'1D Mr. Blankfein says, drawing laughs from the audience. \u8220\'20\'1CIn my case, it\u8217\'20\'19s read the newspaper.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 So, is he reading the paper himself now? \u8220\'20\'1CI am,\u8221\'20\'1D he says. \u8220\'20\'1CNot every paper, but the papers.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 \u8212\'20\'14 William Alden\par \par \uc2 11:16 A.M. | A World War II Analogy\par \par \uc2 Mr. Blankfein offers an analogy on the state of the economy.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CI think we\u8217\'20\'19re like where the U.S. was and world was in 1944 when we were still fighting,\u8221\'20\'1D he says. \u8220\'20\'1CWe hadn\u8217\'20\'19t resolved how we were going to finish the war, but we already knew the war was going to be over.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 He adds, \u8220\'20\'1CAt that point, we were already preparing for the post-war world.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 \u8212\'20\'14 William Alden\par \par \uc2 11:10 A.M. | If Lawmakers Were Business People\par \par \uc2 Mr. Blankfein has been making the rounds in Washington lately as lawmakers haggle over the fiscal situation. His takeaway? The nation\u8217\'20\'19s capital is a \u8220\'20\'1Cbizarre world,\u8221\'20\'1D he says.\par \par \uc2 The nature of the negotiation is alien to the business world. If politicians were business people, Mr. Blankfein says, \u8220\'20\'1CI would say there would be a 100 percent chance of an agreement.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Any compromise, he says, would probably involve \u8220\'20\'1Ca good dose of austerity.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 \u8212\'20\'14 William Alden\par \par \uc2 11:00 A.M. | Blankfein on the New Wall Street\par \par \uc2 Lloyd C. Blankfein\uc2 , the chief of \uc2 Goldman Sachs\uc2 , is answering questions from Mr. Sorkin. Mr. Blankfein endorsed higher tax rates in an {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://online.wsj.com/article/SB10001424127887324894104578114932367361810.html"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 opinion article published in The Wall Street Journal}}}\uc2  last month.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CI believe that tax increases, especially for the wealthiest, are appropriate, but only if they are joined by serious cuts in discretionary spending and entitlements.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 On the Agenda: What\u8217\'20\'19s really new on Wall Street? Have the pressures and regulations \u8212\'20\'14 national and global \u8212\'20\'14 effected change? Have we seen a reduction in systemic risk? Are financial institutions well-positioned to provide liquidity for the economy of the coming decade?\par \par \uc2 \u8212\'20\'14 Eric Owles\par \par \uc2 10:30 A.M. | Coffee!\par \par \uc2 We\u8217\'20\'19re breaking for coffee, but we\u8217\'20\'19ll back in 30 minutes with \uc2 Lloyd C. Blankfein\uc2 , the chief executive of Goldman Sachs. Submit you questions and comments for the panel on \uc2 Twitter\uc2  at {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://twitter.com/search?q=%23DBConf&src=hash"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 #DBConf}}}\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 \u8212\'20\'14 Eric Owles\par \par \uc2 10:26 A.M. | Taxing A-Rod?\par \par \uc2 What would a tax increase on the highest earners look like? Many of these people are sports or entertainment figures, Mr. Gordon says.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CIt does not change economic growth to tax Alex Rodriguez or Oprah Winfrey at \u8212\'20\'14 forget 39.6 percent \u8212\'20\'14 how about 50 percent?\u8221\'20\'1D he says. \u8220\'20\'1CThere\u8217\'20\'19s a huge opportunity to raise revenue there.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 \u8212\'20\'14 William Alden\par \par \uc2 10:15 A.M. | A \u8216\'20\'18Point About Power\u8217\'20\'19\par \par \uc2 Mr. Hubbard delivers a laugh line: \u8220\'20\'1CMy colleagues have made Power Points, and what I wanted to do was make a point about power.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Getting serious, he warns about politics.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CThe idea of declinism has always been fashionable,\u8221\'20\'1D he says. \u8220\'20\'1CFactually, if you look at history, virtually no great power declined because of some exogenous shift in its productivity. What happened in the stumble and the fall was politics not keeping up with economics.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 \u8212\'20\'14 William Alden\par \par \uc2 10:04 A.M. | Dueling Visions on Growth\par \par \uc2 With all the talk about ways to stimulate the economy, Washington, D.C., \u8220\'20\'1Cfeels these days like an economics insane asylum,\u8221\'20\'1D Mr. Bernstein says.\par \par \uc2 But he lays out his own ideas for growth, using plenty of charts. Mr. Bernstein challenges the argument for tax reform and spending cuts. \u8220\'20\'1CI think this is the wrong to-do list, big time.\u8221\'20\'1D Instead, he says, the nation should focus on \u8220\'20\'1Ccapital investment, particularly in I.T., with investment in public goods.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CThe fact that we have the most unequal income distribution that we\u8217\'20\'19ve had since the 1920s also factors into this,\u8221\'20\'1D he adds. \u8220\'20\'1CIt has to do with an underinvestment in the have-nots and a blocking of their economic opportunity.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 But Mr. Hubbard, a prominent conservative, takes a different view, saying: \u8220\'20\'1CTax reform is probably the biggest single weapon we have to encourage growth.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Still, Mr. Hubbard outlines some ideas that were absent from Mr. Romney\u8217\'20\'19s campaign platform. \u8220\'20\'1CIf we move to a consumption tax in the U.S. that\u8217\'20\'19s progressive, we could probably increase output on the order of 7 to 10 percent,\u8221\'20\'1D he said.\par \par \uc2 Tax reform, he says, \u8220\'20\'1Chas to be a 2013 discussion.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 \u8212\'20\'14 William Alden\par \par \uc2 9:44 A.M. | The Economic To-Do List\par \par \uc2 Jared Bernstein, a senior fellow at the \uc2 Center on Budget and Policy Priorities\uc2 ; \uc2 Robert Gordon\uc2 , a professor of economics at \uc2 Northwestern University\uc2 ; and \uc2 R. Glenn Hubbard\uc2 , dean of the Columbia University Graduate School of Business, offer their predictions for the next four years of macroeconomics. Moderated by {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/people/l/annie_lowrey/index.html"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Annie Lowrey}}}\uc2 , an economic policy reporter for The \uc2 New York Times\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Mr. Bernstein, an economic adviser to Vice President Joseph R. Biden Jr., wrote {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.nytimes.com/2012/12/06/opinion/a-slow-growth-rate-is-the-real-threat.html"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 an Op-Ed in The New York Times}}}\uc2  this month, arguing for policies to raise America\u8217\'20\'19s underlying growth rate.\par \par \uc2 Mr. Gordon said in a {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.nber.org/papers/w18315"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 recent research paper}}}\uc2  that the gains from the Internet have lessened in the last eight years.\par \par \uc2 And Mr. Hubbard, who was a top adviser to Mitt Romney, wrote an {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.glennhubbard.net/commentary-and-op-eds/425-fiscal-cliff-standoff-is-a-debate-about-the-size-of-government.html"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Op-Ed in the Financial Times}}}\uc2  recently arguing that the current fiscal debate is really a discussion about the size of the federal government.\par \par \uc2 On the Agenda: Following the outcome of the general election, what is the macro outlook for the next four years? What is Wall Street\u8217\'20\'19s response to the promises of the new administration? What are the expectations for fiscal policy? What should be on the to-do list for the administration and Congress?\par \par \uc2 \u8212\'20\'14 Eric Owles\par \par \uc2 9:40 A.M. | Surveying the Technology World\par \par \uc2 Everyone strongly suspects Apple is working on a television, which may come out in 2014 or maybe next year, Mr. Andreessen says.\par \par \uc2 There is a feeling in Silicon Valley that Apple has to crystallize the new category of smart TVs. The rhythm of the industry right now, he says, is that Apple has to go first. But other companies, like \uc2 Google\uc2  and \uc2 Microsoft\uc2 , will quickly follow.\par \par \uc2 Will Apple continue to lead? Mr. Andreessen says the company has to keep pumping out exciting new products. It is an issue Apple has confronted before, with \uc2 Steven P. Jobs\uc2  and without him. And it is one the company has to consider again.\par \par \uc2 He praises \uc2 Google\uc2  as firing on all cylinders. Android phones and tablets are doing really well, and heck, he\u8217\'20\'19s even excited about the self-driving car. (Like a kid in a candy store, Mr. Andreessen bops in his seat as he notes that the self-driving car is legal in California.)\par \par \uc2 Privacy laws: Before forging ahead, politicians should carefully study the effects of legislation that would govern how data is collected from users of Internet products.\par \par \uc2 Who\u8217\'20\'19s the next \uc2 Steve Jobs\uc2 ? Mr. Andreessen \u8212\'20\'14 who very quickly disclaimed any claim to the title \u8212\'20\'14 says he doesn\u8217\'20\'19t think there is a new one. But he says Mr. Jobs is the model entrepreneurs in the Valley idolize, for having created and run the company for the long term, with users first in mind.\par \par \uc2 \u8212\'20\'14 Michael J. de la Merced\par \par \uc2 9:32 A.M. | Andreessen on a Tech Bubble\par \par \uc2 Mr. Andreessen disputes the notion of a tech bubble. In some ways, he argues, the public market right now hates technology.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1COne interpretation is, we\u8217\'20\'19re in a tech depression,\u8221\'20\'1D he says. He notes that major technology companies like Intel and Cisco are trading at \u8220\'20\'1Cgenerational lows,\u8221\'20\'1D with price-to-earnings ratios at rock-bottom levels not seen since the 1970s.\par \par \uc2 Some tech giants are troubled by company-specific issues, he concedes. But there may be other issues at work.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CI think we\u8217\'20\'19re still dealing with broken trust from the 2000 crash,\u8221\'20\'1D he says. \u8220\'20\'1CThe 2000 crash was traumatizing.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 And just when it looked like we were rebuilding that trust, he says, the financial crisis happened.\par \par \uc2 In some ways, though, that\u8217\'20\'19s O.K., he adds. It lets companies focus on their work, something that Mr. Andreessen says is an attitude his firm encourages, in part by delaying initial public offerings for as long as possible.\par \par \uc2 Well, what about Groupon, Mr. Sorkin asks? Mr. Andreessen declines to comment.\par \par \uc2 Hewlett-Packard\uc2  is another topic Mr. Andreessen repeatedly ducks, since he is a director of the troubled tech company.\par \par \uc2 \u8212\'20\'14 Michael J. de la Merced\par \par \uc2 9:25 A.M. | Andreessen on Jobs and Unions\par \par \uc2 Is there a place for unions in the economy? Mr. Andreessen says, \u8220\'20\'1CI think there\u8217\'20\'19s a time and a place when the economy is functioning.\u8221\'20\'1D But in some ways it makes more sense when the country has more of a blue-collar economy than a white-collar one.\par \par \uc2 But, Mr. Andreessen says, \u8220\'20\'1CI do think there\u8217\'20\'19s something of a jobs crisis.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 He illustrates the difference between Silicon Valley and the rest of the economy this way: \u8220\'20\'1CThe old joke is, you can get a dozen job offers without getting out of your parking spot.\u8221\'20\'1D He adds, \u8220\'20\'1CIt\u8217\'20\'19s the ultimate job market of all time.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Mr. Sorkin asks what his two 2-year-olds should study in college if they want to make sure they can become gainfully employed. Mr. Andreessen says that math or science skills will be enormously valuable.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CA degree in English, I\u8217\'20\'19m sure it\u8217\'20\'19s great,\u8221\'20\'1D the investor says, \u8220\'20\'1Cbut the average college graduate with a degree in English can go work in a shoe store.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 The American dream has long been about going to college and then getting a productive job. But that is now a misconception, Mr. Andreessen says. \u8220\'20\'1CIt\u8217\'20\'19s not reflective of how the economy actually works.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 \u8212\'20\'14 Michael J. de la Merced\par \par \uc2 9:20 A.M. | \u8216\'20\'18I\u8217\'20\'19m Pro-Gridlock,\u8217\'20\'19 Andreessen Says\par \par \uc2 Mr. Sorkin asks Mr. Andreessen about his comment that the nation should go over the fiscal cliff. Mr. Andreeseen grins and says, \u8220\'20\'1CI\u8217\'20\'19m pro-gridlock.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Mr. Andreeseen, a free-market enthusiast, says he prefers the government to do less. There are going to be several crises in the next 25 Congressional cycles, he says. There will be fiscal cliffs and debt ceiling battles, and it is good for the country to fight.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CThe last thing I want is for our politicians to band together and come up with a grand solution,\u8221\'20\'1D Mr. Andreessen says. The last time Democrats and Republicans banded together, he adds, was the war on Iraq. That elicits a soft \u8220\'20\'1Cooh\u8221\'20\'1D from the crowd.\par \par \uc2 \u8212\'20\'14 Michael J. de la Merced\par \par \uc2 9:09 A.M. | Andreessen on the Triumph of Software\par \par \uc2 Marc Andreessen\uc2 , of the venture capital firm Andreessen Horowitz, and a co-founder of the first major Web browser, Netscape Navigator, is answering questions from Mr. Sorkin.\par \par \uc2 Earlier this year, Nicole Perlroth of The Times reported that the speed with which the venture firm \u8220\'20\'1Chas rocketed to the top ranks has served as {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.nytimes.com/2012/07/23/business/venture-capital-firms-once-discreet-learn-the-promotional-game.html"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 a case study in successful self-promotion}}}\uc2 .\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 \u8212\'20\'14 Eric Owles\par \par \uc2 9:08 A.M. | Treasury Secretary Dimon?\par \par \uc2 Mr. Sorkin brings up \uc2 Warren E. Buffett\uc2 \u8217\'20\'19s recent comment that Mr. Dimon would make an excellent Treasury secretary, leading him to visibly squirm a little before issuing a fairly stout denial.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CI\u8217\'20\'19m flattered,\u8221\'20\'1D he says, \u8220\'20\'1Cbut I\u8217\'20\'19m not suited to it.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Mr. Dimon adds, \u8220\'20\'1CI don\u8217\'20\'19t think a C.E.O. from Wall Street can get confirmed,\u8221\'20\'1D drawing a few chuckles from the audience.\par \par \uc2 \u8212\'20\'14 Michael J. de la Merced\par \par \uc2 9:06 A.M. | Dimon on the \u8216\'20\'18London Whale\u8217\'20\'19\par \par \uc2 When Mr. Sorkin asks about \uc2 JPMorgan\uc2 \u8217\'20\'19s health, Mr. Dimon says that the trouble caused by the trading incident at the firm\u8217\'20\'19s chief investment office \u8212\'20\'14 arising when a huge position taken on by a trader known as the London Whale went sour \u8212\'20\'14 has been largely limited.\par \par \uc2 While it did lead to a shake-up of the firm\u8217\'20\'19s executive ranks some, Mr. Dimon says, it did not cause much damage.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CI think that the Whale accelerated certain things,\u8221\'20\'1D he says. \u8220\'20\'1CIt caused a little turmoil.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 The team itself is excellent, with a deep bench, Mr. Dimon adds.\par \par \uc2 \u8212\'20\'14 Michael J. de la Merced\par \par \uc2 9:03 A.M. | Dimon Defends Bank Lobbyists\par \par \uc2 After Mr. Sorkin asks about \uc2 JPMorgan\uc2 \u8217\'20\'19s \u8220\'20\'1Carmy of lobbyists,\u8221\'20\'1D Mr. Dimon defends the banking industry\u8217\'20\'19s efforts. He says that of the 7,000 lobbying organizations in Washington, those working for the banking industry represent a small part of that number.\par \par \uc2 He mounts a defense rooted in the First Amendment, saying banks also have a right to have their concerns heard.\par \par \uc2 Mr. Dimon also rebuffs any insinuation that Wall Street has an unfair stranglehold on Washington. Banks, he says, can and should speak out, just as much as any other group.\par \par \uc2 \u8212\'20\'14 Michael J. de la Merced\par \par \uc2 9:00 A.M. | Dimon on Fracking\par \par \uc2 Mr. Dimon tells the audience that he once spoke to a JPMorgan director, bemoaning the lack of an energy policy at the firm. The director responded, \u8220\'20\'1CWe do have one. It\u8217\'20\'19s just a bad one.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 The banking chief says that hydraulic fracturing, the drilling process commonly known as fracking, allows for an energy revolution.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CThe experts tell me, and I\u8217\'20\'19m told it\u8217\'20\'19s been done this way for 30 years,\u8221\'20\'1D he says. \u8220\'20\'1CCertainly safer than deep drilling in the gulf, safer than going overseas to fight wars.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Mr. Dimon says he \u8220\'20\'1Cwould be in favor, over time, for some sort of increase that would resemble a carbon tax.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 \u8212\'20\'14 Michael J. de la Merced\par \par \uc2 8:57 A.M. | Dimon on Bank Scandals and Compensation\par \par \uc2 When Mr. Sorkin asks Mr. Dimon about the spate of recent banking scandals, including the one that led \uc2 HSBC\uc2  to agree to pay a fine of nearly $2 billion, Mr. Dimon responds that while there are a few bad actors, such behavior is not endemic within his institution or the industry.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CNo one at \uc2 JPMorgan\uc2  condones bad behavior,\u8221\'20\'1D he says. He adds that when he was the chief executive of Bank One in Chicago, two sitting governors went to jail.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CYou can\u8217\'20\'19t tar an entire institution because of a few bad people,\u8221\'20\'1D he says.\par \par \uc2 With the conversation pivoting to compensation, Mr. Dimon says that while he will not disclose specifics, compensation will be measured this year. No special parachutes or other controversial payouts are in the offing, he says.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CKnow where the best opportunities are?\u8221\'20\'1D Mr. Dimon asks. He knocks the table next to him. \u8220\'20\'1CIt\u8217\'20\'19s right here.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 He bemoans some problems, like troubles with the H-1B visa program that he says are shipping off qualified young immigrants back to their home countries.\par \par \uc2 That said, Mr. Dimon says there are plenty of opportunities elsewhere, which he says he is qualified to know, having recently traveled to China and India.\par \par \uc2 \u8212\'20\'14 Michael J. de la Merced\par \par \uc2 8:50 A.M. | Dimon and Obama\par \par \uc2 Mr. Sorkin asks Mr. Dimon how his relationship is with the White House. \u8220\'20\'1CIt\u8217\'20\'19s fine,\u8221\'20\'1D the banking chief responds, drawing laughs from the audience.\par \par \uc2 Mr. Dimon praises President Obama for reaching out and for going to the Business Roundtable. \u8220\'20\'1CCollaboration is always better,\u8221\'20\'1D he says. \u8220\'20\'1CIt\u8217\'20\'19s better for the country. If we can\u8217\'20\'19t be great, we won\u8217\'20\'19t be great.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 That said, Mr. Dimon adds, Wall Street will be able to adapt no matter the circumstances.\par \par \uc2 \u8212\'20\'14 Michael J. de la Merced\par \par \uc2 8:40 A.M. | Dimon on the Global Climate for Finance\par \par \uc2 Jamie Dimon\uc2 , the chief of \uc2 JPMorgan Chase\uc2 , is answering questions from Mr. Sorkin. Mr. Dimon has been {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://dealbook.nytimes.com/2012/11/19/jpmorgan-names-a-new-chief-financial-officer/"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 shaking up the bank\u8217\'20\'19s management}}}\uc2  after a multibillion-dollar trading loss this year.\par \par \uc2 \u8212\'20\'14 Eric Owles\par \par \uc2 8:33 A.M. | Welcome From Sulzberger and Sorkin\par \par \uc2 Arthur Sulzberger Jr\uc2 ., the chairman of The New York Times, and \uc2 Andrew Ross Sorkin\uc2 , editor at large of DealBook, are welcoming the crowd at The Times Center.\par \par \uc2 \u8212\'20\'14 Eric Owles\par \par \uc2 7:09 AM | Registration Has Begun\par \par \uc2 If you are unable to join us at The Times Center, you can watch the proceedings on CNBC\u8217\'20\'19s Squawk Box with Becky Quick, Joe Kernen and \uc2 Andrew Ross Sorkin\uc2  from 7 to 8:40 a.m. Submit you questions and comments for the panel on \uc2 Twitter\uc2  at {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://twitter.com/search?q=%23DBConf&src=hash"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 #DBConf}}}\uc2 . If @DealBook favorites your reply, it will appear on a video screen at the conference.\par \par \uc2 \u8212\'20\'14 Eric Owles\par \par \uc2 * {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://dealbook.nytimes.com/2013/10/28/frenzy-of-deals-once-expected-seems-to-fizzle/"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Frenzy of Deals, Once Expected, Seems to Fizzle}}}\par \par \uc2 * {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://dealbook.nytimes.com/2013/10/10/stocks-rally-talks-stall-then-skepticism-returns/"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Stocks Rally, Talks Stall, Then Skepticism Returns }}}\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0