ribute by email or post to the web.   \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Working as a new graduate for the United Nations in Nairobi, Pratik Bhatnagar received some surprising advice - that working for a non-governmental organisation was the best way to learn how to run a business and gain management skills.\par \par \uc2 Mr Bhatnagar did not follow his boss's suggestion, heading off on a career in consulting - but he never forgot it.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Two decades on, and with postgraduate degrees from \uc2 Yale University\uc2  and IMD, the Swiss business school, the 42-year-old Indian national now sees the wisdom in his mentor's words.\par \par \uc2 "Working in not-for-profit organisations is much more intense. There is resource constraint all the time," says Mr Bhatnagar, a director at the \uc2 World Wide Fund for Nature\uc2 , the conservation charity, since 2011.\par \par \uc2 "There is flexibility to contribute across functions and you get responsibility sooner. There is great use of my general management skills."\par \par \uc2 While many senior executives who move into the international public sector find their new roles similarly exhilarating and stimulating, they also often find the transition difficult.\par \par \uc2 "Private sector boards focus primarily on strategy. At not-for-profit organisations, strategy is often not open to debate. It is defined by the nature of the organisation," says Will Dawkins, head of the board practice at \uc2 Spencer Stuart\uc2 , the executive search firm.\par \par \uc2 "Roles tend to be more operational and focused on delivery than they are in the private sector where it is possible to revise the whole strategy. Therefore, it can seem narrower."\par \par \uc2 The culture and management style is also often very different, he says: "There is usually less hierarchy in the not-for-profit sector and less opportunity to lead by command. People need to use persuasion and influence.\par \par \uc2 "Arriving at decisions frequently takes more time. The more assertive people can find this enormously frustrating," Mr Dawkins says.\par \par \uc2 When Rachel Parr, then a finance vice-president at \uc2 GlaxoSmithKline\uc2 , announced she was moving to \uc2 Save the Children\uc2  after more than 20 years at the drugs company, some of her colleagues told her the NGO world would drive her mad.\par \par \uc2 Ms Parr, 48, acting chief operating officer at \uc2 Save the Children\uc2 , was attracted by the breadth of the role at a smaller and more agile organisation and had also wanted to work closely with a chief executive.\par \par \uc2 She had the benefit of understanding the world she was entering: she had had contact with the international charity at GSK and had undertaken voluntary work in the not-for-profit sector for most of her adult life.\par \par \uc2 She says it is unlikely she would have received GSK's high-level training - from HR and finance to marketing and IT - in the voluntary sector.\par \par \uc2 "I have proved to myself that my skill set is transferable. It has opened me up to new sectors. There is a lot in my kit bag that I can apply."\par \par \uc2 She dismisses the idea that working for a charity is a soft option. But she acknowledges that her CV is not as straightforward as it was and says she will have to decide in the next three to four years whether to switch back to the private sector: "Beyond that, you've committed yourself to the public sector," she says.\par \par \uc2 While it is possible to return to the business world, it is hard to go back to a promotion, cautions Mr Dawkins: "The job you get might look suspiciously like the one you left."\par \par \uc2 However, more professionals than ever appear to be moving fairly seamlessly between the public and private sectors. Ann Grant, formerly a UK diplomat and now a vice-chairman at Standard Chartered Bank, (see profile on next page) says she very rarely hears colleagues under 40, many of them African or Asian, talking in terms of "private" or "public" sector.\par \par \uc2 "What they want is an interesting career in interesting places, and something that will develop them," she says. "I think a lot more will move between sectors."\par \par \uc2 While Peter Gasson, 46, had long considered working for an NGO, joining WWF China was a sound career move. The Canadian former senior BT executive joined as chief operating officer before being promoted last year to chief executive, his first chief executive role. "The WWF brand is so strong I knew it would look good on my CV," he says.\par \par \uc2 It also took him to Beijing and its "hot job market", giving him "great exposure". With valuable knowledge of the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 , colleagues leaving WWF often land good jobs in \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Mr Gasson says what has surprised him most is the complexity of his job and of WWF's mission.\par \par \uc2 Like many who work for NGOs, he must balance multiple stakeholders - from forestry companies and scientists to donors and several Chinese government ministries.\par \par \uc2 He has also had to adapt to running an organisation in which decisions are not governed by profitability and to a world where there are "no right answers".\par \par \uc2 "You think science is clear cut but it isn't," he says. "We have robust, iterative scientific debates until we reach a decision. The complexity has increased dramatically."\par \par \uc2 But while it often takes longer to achieve successes, he says the feeling of fulfilment is greater and lasts much longer.\par \par \uc2 Operating within new forms of governance, both internally and externally, is another common challenge, says James Campion, a director at Michael Page, the recruitment company. He gives the example of an executive in the public sector working across nine different operations who has to attend more than 200 board level meetings a year.\par \par \uc2 Nevertheless, competition for senior roles has become even more fierce in the difficult global economy, he says.\par \par \uc2 Lucinda Read, an HR partner at the \uc2 European Bank for Reconstruction and Development\uc2 , agrees. The bank, like others, is often overwhelmed with strong candidates.\par \par \uc2 She says staff, who come from more than 50 countries, value the collegial nature of a truly multicultural, multilateral agency. While London-based, employees gain valuable experience in often risky emerging markets from eastern Europe to central Asia and now North Africa.\par \par \uc2 Catherine Fearon, 43, was inspired to work for multilateral organisations and missions in the former Yugoslavia, Afghanistan, and Sudan by her experiences as a young person in her native Northern Ireland.\par \par \uc2 A former president of the student union at Queen's University Belfast, she worked for a women's political party during the 1990s peace negotiations, gaining an understanding of differences and conflict that she has been able to apply elsewhere.\par \par \uc2 Moving between exacting postings, now at ambassador level, she says she has formed strong friendships and that it is important to keep in touch, have a support system and to take regular exercise.\par \par \uc2 "The scale of what agencies are trying to do is mind-boggling. You face impossible tasks," she says.\par \par \uc2 Preferring employment contracts that last for one to two years, she starts looking for her next position six or eight months in advance: "You have to get your CV out there. I don't walk into jobs but I have never been out of work."\par \par \uc2 Mr Bhatnagar, at the WWF in Geneva, says former classmates and more recent IMD graduates are increasingly interested in what he is doing.\par \par \uc2 He has been able to draw on his business school skills and examine value chains at WWF more closely, looking at problems in new ways: "I have become more creative," he says. "IMD friends want to learn from my experiences. There is a shift in the mindset."\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CO\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 wwfni : \uc2 World Wide Fund for Nature International\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\as