ntbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 English\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CY\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Copyright 2013, The Washington Post Co.  All Rights Reserved.   \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 TRIPOLI, Libya \u8212\'20\'14 Huge placards proclaim "Yes to disarming," "No to a state of militias," on the building housing the Tripoli offices of Mellitah, a joint venture between Libya and Eni, the Italian oil and gas group.\par \par \uc2 They are a reminder of two days of deadly clashes between rival armed groups from the towns of Zintan and Zuara over who should guard Mellitah's oil and gas complex in western Libya. The firefight last month left at least one dead and several injured. It also disrupted production and caused a temporary halt in natural gas exports to Italy before the army finally came in to restore order.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Violent incidents such as those at Mellitah have become a recurrent feature for the hydrocarbons industry in Libya since the 2011 fall of Moammar Gaddafi, the former president.\par \par \uc2 Though Libya has managed to restore oil production to pre-revolution levels of some 1.6 million barrels a day, the weakness of its government and the proliferation of armed groups have transformed the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  for international companies working in the oil-rich North African country.\par \par \uc2 Heavily armed militias are invading oil fields, locals demanding jobs are blockading facilities and protests are closing down export terminals. And then there are the regional concerns in the wake of the attack on an oil facility in neighboring Algeria earlier this year.\par \par \uc2 The disruptions to production have cost the OPEC member about $1 billion over the past five months, Abdulbari Ali al-Arousi, the oil minister, told the Financial Times. "When there are sit-ins, oil fields shut down," he said. "The losses are the result of failure to produce and to export. We try to resolve these problems through dialogue and discussion."\par \par \uc2 The government has beefed up its Petroleum Facilities Guard, which now numbers 18,000 men, many of them former militia members who are being integrated into the military. But still, officials say there are no easy answers to the security problems in the chaotic and near-lawless country, still awash with weapons.\par \par \uc2 "Security is manageable, but things are very volatile," said the country manager of an international company. "Expatriates are not being targeted, but you can get caught up in a bad situation. It is a completely different operation from before the [fall of Gaddafi]. Management cannot force anything on the staff."\par \par \uc2 Part of the problem is that some of the local militias that guarded oil installations during the war to overthrow Gaddafi now feel entitled to jobs and other benefits, say diplomats and industry insiders. Before the revolution, stringent security was not necessary.\par \par \uc2 "It was a private army situation [during the revolution], but now the government is taking over security at oil installations," said a western diplomat. "Those people have to be offered something or integrated. The government is doing it, but it is a long process."\par \par \uc2 In March, Waha Oil, owned by the state-run \uc2 National Oil Corporation\uc2  in partnership with \uc2 ConocoPhillips\uc2 , Hess and \uc2 Marathon Oil\uc2 , cancelled a contract with a private-sector oil services company after a 17-day blockade by protesters who said it took away their jobs.\par \par \uc2 Companies should consider \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  programs for local communities, said Arousi. "They can offer health and educational services, or train people or lay on some transport, perhaps a bus or an ambulance," he said.\par \par \uc2 Dealing with rowdy militias in the chaotic aftermath of the revolution is not their only challenge. Many fear rising Islamist militancy in the borderless Sahara desert. Though Islamist radicals have not targeted oil installations in Libya, presumed militants killed a U.S. ambassador in the summer in the eastern city of Benghazi.\par \par \uc2 In January, \uc2 al-Qaeda\uc2  affiliates attacked a gas complex in In Amenas operated by BP and \uc2 Statoil\uc2  just across the border in Algeria. Scores of people, including staff and militants, were killed after a stand-off that sent ripples of fear through the industry in Libya.\par \par \uc2 "In Amenas was a game changer," said the oil executive. "It has been a wake-up call for the Libyan government. Before the revolution, oil fields were not protected. They had guards, but they lacked training and resources. Now the government is taking measures, with more guards and intelligence-gathering, especially with the prevailing political \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  and the situation in Mali and Algeria."\par \par \uc2 Fears remain, however, over the training, efficacy and loyalty to their army commanders of militia members drafted to protect oil facilities.\par \par \uc2 "Try telling a guy who has been wearing shorts and flip-flops and looting buildings for a year and half, 'You can't do that any more. Now you get 800 dinars and you follow orders,'\u8201\'20\'09" said the western diplomat. "It's a difficult process."\par \par \uc2 \u8212\'20\'14 Financial Times\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b IN\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 i13 : \uc2 Crude Oil/Natural Gas | i1 : \uc2 Energy\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 gpol : \uc2 Domestic Politics | gcat : \uc2 Political/General News | gpir : \uc2 Politics/International Relations\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\asp