ay.  Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning.   All Rights Reserved.   \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Nine in 10 consumers say they would boycott companies they believe are being irresponsible, says an international "\b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 " report out Wednesday.\par \par \uc2 That's not just theoretical: More than half of consumers surveyed in 10 countries say they've refused to buy a product in the past year because of what they saw as bad corporate behavior, says the report by marketing and public relations agency \uc2 Cone Communications\uc2 , which has specialties in cause marketing and \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 That might not bode well for Gap, \uc2 Wal-Mart\uc2  and other U.S. retailers that so far have not signed a labor-backed plan on factory safety while they work on alternative plans.\par \par \uc2 Pressure for a factory safety deal intensified after a Bangladesh factory making clothes for major retailers collapsed in April, killing 1,127.\par \par \uc2 Most major Europe-based companies and U.S. retailer \uc2 Abercrombie & Fitch\uc2  have agreed to a labor-backed plan calling for independent safety audits that will be made public and for the companies to pay for safety improvements in factories.\par \par \uc2 Gap, which has held itself out as a \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social\b0 \highlight\uc2 - \b \highlight22\uc2 responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  leader, is being targeted the most aggressively by backers of the labor plan. The company, however, says it's pursuing its own safety initiative and will not agree to the unions' proposal unless its liability concerns are addressed.\par \par \uc2 Ian Bassin, general counsel of the global activist group Avaaz, which is pushing the plan, says Gap is trying to make the plan unenforceable. Avaaz, which says it has 21 million members that it taps for campaigns, is leading the charge against Gap using social media.\par \par \uc2 The group has launched a \uc2 Facebook\uc2  and \uc2 Twitter\uc2  campaign to pressure Gap to sign the safety accord, and about 1.1 million people had signed onto the campaign as of late Tuesday.\par \par \uc2 Avaaz also has organized protests at Gap's headquarters in San Francisco and showed up for the retailer's shareholder meeting there on Tuesday.\par \par \uc2 Cone's survey of 10,000 consumers in the U.S., Canada, Brazil, the U.K., Germany, France, Russia, China, India and Japan found them increasingly using social media to talk about companies, with more than a third using social media to spread positive information about a company, and a fourth spreading negative company news.\par \par \uc2 Gap spokesman Bill Chandler says his company has a "history of taking action wherever we operate," citing efforts to improve working conditions in Haiti, Vietnam, Cambodia and Bangladesh.\par \par \uc2 He says that its efforts for \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  are why the retailer is being singled out.\par \par \uc2 Bassin says that's only fair. "If you put yourself out there as the paragon of the highest standards and ideals, and you fail to live up to them -- and are one of the laggards -- then you are going to face harsh criticism. Your reputation is going to drop precipitously, even if you are at the forefront."\par \par \uc2 Cone Executive Vice President Jonathan Yohannan says that though Gap has been active on responsibility issues, including the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  and diversity, it is not much known as a \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social\b0 \highlight\uc2 -\b \highlight22\uc2 responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  leader outside of retailing, nor outside the United States.\par \par \uc2 Companies such as \uc2 Marks & Spencer\uc2 , Patagonia and \uc2 Whole Foods Market\uc2  are better examples of retailers known as leaders globally, he says.\par \par \uc2 Cone says that nearly 90% of consumers consider \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  when deciding where to shop and that it's important for retailers to communicate about how products are made. The report says that a growing concern for consumers in the survey was economic development -- 38% cited it as their top concern, up 4 percentage points since 2011 -- followed by human rights, poverty and hunger.\par \par \uc2 The report also shows, however, that although consumers say they would boycott companies they see as guilty of bad behavior, they will only favor one they see as better-behaving if the price and quality of its products are about the same.\par \par \uc2 Still, the overall effect could be higher prices. "Retailers may "need to rethink the $5 T-shirt," says Cone research and insights chief Alison DaSilva. "It may not be $5 anymore."\par \par \uc2 Philip Rooke\uc2 , CEO of the custom T-shirt site Spreadshirt.com, says he can tell what conditions T-shirts are probably made under by the price -- especially when some are sold at retail for less than his wholesale price.\par \par \uc2 "In the end, someone selling a T-shirt for $1.50 is taking big risks," says Rooke. "It is not possible to do it ethically."\par \par \uc2 People may love low prices but fail to realize "the impact of what they're doing" when they buy, Rooke says. "Those factories have very poor workers' rights or very poor safety."\par \par \uc2 Studies and interviews show that while consumers care, their zeal for deals may outweigh that in the long run.\par \par \uc2 "It sounds good and makes good copy (for a retailer) to say that if you pay 25 cents more, all the world's problems would be solved, but it's never that simple," says Vinod Rangarajan, a sourcing and retail strategist at consulting firm Kurt Salmon. "Do you give up on your (profit) margin, or pass it on to the consumer? Is the consumer willing to pay more?"\par \par \uc2 That can depend on the shopper and what she's buying. A 2012 study by \uc2 Harvard University\uc2  and \uc2 Massachusetts Institute of Technology\uc2  researchers looked at "fair-trade certified" clothing with a label certifying that certain factory labor and safety standards were observed. It found that someone looking for the best buy on a package of socks is not so inclined to buy the slightly more expensive "fair labor" option, while someone buying a pricier item might spend more for a fair-trade certification.\par \par \uc2 Rangarajan says it can be easier for smaller and higher-end retailers to shift from very-low-cost suppliers. Mass-market and discount retailers often can't get away with raising prices.\par \par \uc2 The move towards inexpensive "fast fashion" in the past few years has coincided with the growth of garment production in Bangladesh. That nation has moved from being the eighth-biggest garment exporter in 2005 to the fourth in 2011, according to the most recent data available from the \uc2 World Trade Organization\uc2 . Bangladesh accounted for 4.7% of world clothing exports in 2011, up from 2.5% in 2005.\par \par \uc2 Fast fashion, which quickly replicates the latest hot trends, was popularized by \uc2 H&M\uc2 , Forever 21 and Zara.\par \par \uc2 Sonya Sestito, 23, says she would pay a little more for clothes at her favorite stores, which include Forever 21 and \uc2 H&M\uc2 , if she knew the companies were "socially responsible in the way that they gave their workers safe conditions and adequate pay."\par \par \uc2 Still, Sestito may be an exception. Consumers may be troubled by news accounts of unsafe factory conditions, but quickly forget.\par \par \uc2 "Denial is a pretty powerful thing if something is beautiful and you really want it," says consumer psychologist Kit Yarrow.\par \par \uc2 ---\par \par \uc2 Consumers surveyed on boycotting\par \par \uc2 A February survey of consumers in 10 countries showed:\par \par \uc2 27%\par \par \uc2 Believe they have a significant positive impact through purchasing decisions they make.\par \par \uc2 55%\par \par \uc2 Have boycotted a company's products or services in the last year because it behaved irresponsibly.\par \par \uc2 91%\par \par \uc2 Are very likely to switch to a company associated with a good cause if price/quality the same.\par \par \uc2 93%\par \par \uc2 Would be more loyal to a company that supports social or environmental causes.\par \par \uc2 Source Echo Research survey of 10,287 demographically representative adults in 10 countries, including the United States.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b ART\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 