T articles and redistribute by email or post to the web.   \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Marketing can sound woefully fluffy. The language of "emotional engagement", "consumer passion-points" and "key influencers" the industry has become so fond of is a tough sell to senior executives under pressure to deliver hard returns from their investment in advertising.\par \par \uc2 Little wonder that executives at \uc2 Procter & Gamble\uc2  and \uc2 Mondelez International\uc2  have felt able to recently squeeze ad agencies by delaying payments for 75 days and 120 days respectively.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Advertising spending will hit $518bn this year, \uc2 ZenithOptimedia\uc2  estimates, yet as the media face rapid digital, mobile and social changes, brand owners have never been less sure of the returns that investment will yield.\par \par \uc2 It is tempting, then, to ignore a report about "meaningful brands" as more waffle. The idea of a phone, a car, a shampoo or a running shoe having much meaning sounds like an ad executive's outlandishly lofty promise for "a product that will change your life".\par \par \uc2 Yet the Meaningful Brands study released this week by the media buying arm of French marketing group \uc2 Havas\uc2  deserves to be taken more seriously.\par \par \uc2 First, its methodology lends it weight: \uc2 Havas\uc2  asked 134,000 consumers in 23 countries for their views on 700 brands, and set out to define "meaning" by 12 measures of brands' contributions to individuals' quality of life and to wider society. Some metrics were borrowed from \uc2 OECD\uc2  and \uc2 World Bank\uc2  indices of what some call gross national happiness, for what Umair Haque, a Havas Media director, dubs the first attempt to connect human wellbeing with brands.\par \par \uc2 Second, it focuses precisely on the hard numbers that corporate bean-counters like. The 25 brands that consumers deemed "most meaningful" outperformed global equities by 120 per cent in the last decade.\par \par \uc2 Those top brands are not all obvious ones, when measured by usual benchmarks of revenues, market capitalisation or brand value. Apple, for example, is the world's most valuable company - at the time of writing - and tops \uc2 WPP\uc2 's BrandZ list of the world's most valuable brands, but ranks at 22 on the Meaningful Brands list. Other brands - \uc2 Google\uc2  , \uc2 Samsung\uc2 , \uc2 Microsoft\uc2  and \uc2 Sony\uc2  - share the top five spots in the list with \uc2 Nestl\u233\'00\'E9\uc2  ; a reflection, \uc2 Havas\uc2  says, of how technology has empowered consumers.\par \par \uc2 Havas\uc2  diplomatically declines to name the laggards, but \uc2 McDonald's\uc2  , number four on the BrandZ list, is not in its 25 most meaningful. Nor is \uc2 General Motors\uc2  , one of America's biggest advertisers. Financial and energy companies score badly, and despite their global growth, Chinese brands are not breaking through.\par \par \uc2 The third point bolstering the report's credibility is its deeply uncomfortable message for marketers. Most people around the world, \uc2 Havas\uc2  found, would not care if 73 per cent of all brands disappeared. There are even more sobering findings in Europe and the US, where consumers would not care if 92 per cent of brands disappeared.\par \par \uc2 The disconnect has not happened overnight. But what caused it, and how can brands be more meaningful?\par \par \uc2 In mature markets, brand saturation may be part of the problem. You hardly need to spend long in an American supermarket to conclude there are simply too many indifferent brands out there.\par \par \uc2 More importantly, too many brands have been making promises they cannot fulfil. Slightly less than a third of consumers think brands communicate honestly, resulting in growing distrust.\par \par \uc2 After the effort and money spent on \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  programmes, sustainability initiatives and what Michael Porter calls "shared value", an attempt to marry economic and social progress, this is a dispiriting finding.\par \par \uc2 More constructively, the study shows that consumers reward brands that listen to them, provide good quality, innovative products at fair prices; make their lives happier, easier and healthier; and support the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 , the economy and the community. "A new model for human prosperity is emerging, centred around the idea of human potential and wellbeing," Mr Haque says. That is a big claim.\par \par \uc2 But there is nothing fluffy in the correlation between contributing to consumers' wellbeing and being rewarded by consumers and, in turn, by investors. Mr Haque wants to use the data to derive a new financial metric, the "price to wellbeing ratio". Executives may massage earnings, he notes, but "you can't massage meaning".\par \par \uc2 That might even be a way for the marketing community to convince penny-pinching procurement executives it can still be meaningful.\par \par \uc2 Andrew Edgecliffe-Johnson is the \uc2 Financial Times\uc2 ' media editor\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CO\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 dk : \uc2 Mondelez International Inc | prgml : \uc2 The Procter & Gamble Company\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b IN\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 i258 : \uc2 Cosmetics/Toiletries | i41 : \uc2 Food/Beverages/Tobacco | icnp : \uc2 Consumer Goods | ifood : \uc2 Food Products | ipcare : \uc2 Personal Care Products/Appliances\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 cbrand : \uc2 Branding | c31 : \uc2 Marketing/Markets | ccat : \uc2 Corporate/Industrial News | ncat : \uc2 Content Types | nfact : \uc2 Factiva Filters | nfcpin : \uc2 C&E Industry News Filter\cell \pard \q