lpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Even though progress has been made, harnessing commercial self-interest to benefit society will remain problematic, writes Sarah Murray\par \par \uc2 Many argue that in order to transform capitalism so it benefits all of society, companies must stop thinking in terms of corporate philanthropy or traditional CSR (\b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 ) and devise strategies that add greater social value to their profit-driven commercial agendas. The truth is that this is easier said than done.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 This year's Responsible Business Awards - run by Business in the Community (BITC), the UK business-led charity - reflect the struggle to narrow the gap between strategies that are more philanthropic and those that deliver direct value to the bottom line.\par \par \uc2 For example, Big Tick winners in the Enterprise Growth award (see pages 14-15) - which rewards businesses for supporting small enterprises - include Santander UK, the British unit of the Spanish banking group, which uses its funding, knowledge and resources to help more than 1,300 small and medium-sized enterprises (SME) create jobs and drive growth.\par \par \uc2 For Santander, the strategy not only helps the bank contribute to employment and economic growth. It has brought in new customers and raised its share of the UK SME market to more than 5 per cent.\par \par \uc2 The business benefits of some corporate responsibility initiatives are harder to measure. \uc2 EDF Energy\uc2  won a Big Tick in the Inspiring Social Action in Young People category for a programme in London's for-mer Olympic boroughs, where employees volunteer to develop projects ranging from community drama to crime prevention.\par \par \uc2 The benefits to the company are not negligible - the Legacy Champions programme appeals to potential recruits and employees say they have a better understanding of young people and are more proud to work for the company. But the extent to which this underpins \uc2 EDF Energy\uc2 's financial success is harder to quantify.\par \par \uc2 Some changes in corporate strategy - such as the reshaping of supply chains - reflect an understanding that the long-term viability of companies depends on the health of society.\par \par \uc2 When it comes to efforts to address environmental challenges, there are measurable financial benefits in the cost savings made by cutting water and energy consumption or reducing use of resources. With the world's natural resources under increasing pressure, such strategies can be seen as prudent risk management measures.\par \par \uc2 Not all the world's problems align directly with companies' business models - or at least not those that deliver returns in the short to medium term.\par \par \uc2 For companies that want to move faster towards sustainable business models, this isaproblem,in that capital markets tend to reward short-term profitability rather than long-term strategies that support environmental sustainability or a healthy society.\par \par \uc2 Many still believe the primary responsibility of companies is to make money. In a London Business School poll, respondents rated things such as a responsible culture, moral leadership, contributing to long-term economic sustainability and creating an engaging workplace 3.4 and 3.6 out of 5. Maximising financial return to shareholders ranked higher, at 3.7.\par \par \uc2 The difficulty for companies is that, while improving labour conditions in developing country factories supportsthefinancialsustainabilityofthe business, these initiatives require long-term investments that do not necessarily pay off in the next quarter's earnings results.\par \par \uc2 Some argue that while companies make claims about programmes that benefit society or the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 , they have not yet done enough to address the negative impact of commercial operations. For as well as helping solve societal problems, companies can contribute to them. This was recently highlighted by the death of more than 1,100 Bangladeshi workers after a factory complex - from which several UK clothing brands sourced garments - collapsed.\par \par \uc2 Such incidents are generating a wave of anti-corporate activism. This comes after an era in which many of the relationships between companies and non-governmental organisations have been based on collaboration, rather than advocacy or boycotts.\par \par \uc2 These partnerships continue. But frustration is growing on the part of many environmental and human rights activists that, despite progress in some areas, companies are not moving fast enough to reduce their adverse impact on people and the planet.\par \par \uc2 Another unresolved question is the extent to which consumers can play a role in pushing companies towards corporate practices that inflict less harm on communities and the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Some evidence exists of a growing niche of consumers that want to match their ethical and environmental values with their purchases. Armed with online social media tools, many are prepared to become more vocal when they see corporate behaviour of which they disapprove.\par \par \uc2 Yet many shoppers' memories, it seems, are short. A recent opinion poll by Retail Week revealed 44 per cent of UK citizens were no more likely to ask where their clothes were made than they had been before the Bangladesh factory collapse.\par \par \uc2 To judge from one of the awards categories - Customer Engagement on Sustainability - BITC believes one answer is for companies to play a role in changing the way consumers buy and use products.\par \par \uc2 Award winners in this category include \uc2 Coca-Cola\uc2 , which promoted recycling during the London Olympic Games, and EH Booths, the grocery retailer, which uses marketing campaigns to promote sustainable fruit and vegetables, while championing British farmers and local suppliers.\par \par \uc2 One of the Big Tick winners in this category is B&Q, the home improvement retailer. Its One Planet Home programme helps customers cut their environmental impact - showing them how to save energy, save water, grow their own food and start recycling products - while helping them to make greener purchasing choices.\par \par \uc2 B&Q has been removing products from stock - such as gas-powered patio heaters, which emit high levels of carbon dioxide - that do not meet its sustainability goals.\par \par \uc2 How far the corporate sector can go down this path has not been fully tested. Would it be possible for companies to push up the price of goods such as jeans in order to pay for improvements in the conditions in developing country factories? The Retail Week poll would suggest not.\par \par \uc2 So if investors and consumers are not yet prepared to reward companies for strategies that put environmental sustainability and the health of communities ahead of short-term profit and the production of cheap products, who will?\par \par \uc2 Awards such as BITC's can encourage companies to do more. However, it should be remembered that fallen energy giant Enron won numerous environmental awards while engaging in accounting fraud.\par \par \uc2 Until all capitalism's stakeholders, from fund managers and analysts to corporate lobbyists, regulators and consumers, support companies in their socially and environmentally responsible strategies, harnessing commercial self-interest to benefit society will remain an uphill battle.\par \par \uc2 Anita Roddick: Bodyshop founder (1942-2007)\par \par \uc2 'In terms of power and influence you can forget about the church, forget politics. There is no more powerful institution in society than business. The business of business should not be about money, it should be about responsibility. It should be about public good, not private greed'\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 ccsr : \uc2 Corporate Social Responsibility | ccat : \uc2 Corporate/Industrial News | ncat : \uc2 Content Types | nfact : \uc2 Factiva Filters | nfcpex : \uc2 FC&E Executive News Filter\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b RE\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 uk : \uc2 United Kingdom | eecz : \uc2 European Union Countries | eurz : \uc2 Europe | weurz : \uc2 Western Europe\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl1