trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LA\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 English\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CY\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2013 The New York Times Company. All Rights Reserved.   \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Last year, \uc2 Tetra Pak\uc2 , the packaging giant, supplied material for about 173 billion cartons for milk, juice, soups \u8212\'20\'14 even pet food. The multilayered walls of these boxes, which can preserve their contents for months without refrigeration, are on average 75 percent made of a high-grade paper. It is in turn made from wood pulp.\par \par \uc2 A huge number of trees are cut down to feed the company\u8217\'20\'19s needs. Every year, \uc2 Tetra Pak\uc2 \u8217\'20\'19s paper suppliers need to harvest the equivalent of a million hectares, or almost 2.5 million acres, of forest \u8212\'20\'14 an area about the size of Jamaica.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 As it turns out, the appetite for wood of \uc2 Tetra Pak\uc2  and other companies may have a good side. \uc2 Tetra Pak\uc2 , its chief executive, \uc2 Dennis Jonsson\uc2 , said, is determined that the forests from which it obtains paper be managed in a responsible way \u8212\'20\'14 if for no other reason than to ensure that there is an abundant supply in the future.\par \par \uc2 Anything dealing with forests also poses special reputational risks, according to \uc2 Yalmaz Siddiqui\uc2 , senior director for environmental strategy at \uc2 Office Depot\uc2 , which sells enormous quantities of paper for copy machines.\par \par \uc2 \u8216\'20\'18\u8216\'20\'18Forests are an evocative thing,\u8217\'20\'19\u8217\'20\'19 he said. \u8216\'20\'18\u8216\'20\'18As one of the world\u8217\'20\'19s largest resellers of paper, we need to manage the risk from sourcing from this emotionally evocative asset. \u8216\'20\'18\u8216\'20\'18\par \par \uc2 Tetra Pak\uc2 , \uc2 Office Depot\uc2  and other companies want to make sure that there is nothing illegal or otherwise unseemly about the way the wood used for their products is harvested. Last year, \uc2 Tetra Pak\uc2  pulled in revenue of \u8364\'20\'AC11.6 billion, or $15.4 billion, much of it from its food- processing and containers business, and it wants to retain consumers\u8217\'20\'19 confidence.\par \par \uc2 Tetra Pak\uc2  will not use, for instance, wood that has been cut illegally or from places where there are violent disputes taking place with indigenous peoples, the company says.\par \par \uc2 \u8216\'20\'18\u8216\'20\'18We have very strict requirements about what suppliers we will use,\u8217\'20\'19\u8217\'20\'19 Mr. Jonsson said. \u8216\'20\'18\u8216\'20\'18We have turned down some big companies because they don\u8217\'20\'19t live up to our views about how to manage forests.\u8217\'20\'19\u8217\'20\'19\par \par \uc2 For both companies, a key tool for vetting paper suppliers is a global organization called the \uc2 Forest Stewardship Council\uc2 , whose main headquarters is in Bonn. The F.S.C. certifies forests as responsibly managed based on a tough set of criteria, including compliance with applicable laws, not harming the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  and respecting the interests of local communities.\par \par \uc2 Kim Carstensen, the F.S.C.\u8217\'20\'19s general director, said that over the past five years, the number of companies belonging to the organization had quintupled, to about 25,000. Along with \uc2 Tetra Pak\uc2 , other major consumers of forest products like \uc2 Ikea\uc2  and \uc2 Kimberly-Clark\uc2  are also active in the organization, he said.\par \par \uc2 Members are most commonly trying to satisfy the demands of their customers and to fulfill their idea of \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 , he said.\par \par \uc2 Whatever the companies\u8217\'20\'19 motives, trying to win the F.S.C.\u8217\'20\'19s blessing would appear to be a victory for the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  and the local communities.\par \par \uc2 \u8216\'20\'18\u8216\'20\'18Certification focuses your attention on responsible management,\u8217\'20\'19\u8217\'20\'19 Mr. Carstensen said. The organization requires that endangered species and watersheds be protected and that the interests of local communities and forest workers be taken into account.\par \par \uc2 \u8216\'20\'18\u8216\'20\'18All of that makes it almost certain that forest management is better than before,\u8217\'20\'19\u8217\'20\'19 he said.\par \par \uc2 Mr. Carstensen estimates that 10 percent to 12 percent of the world\u8217\'20\'19s commercial forests are now certified. If there is a disappointment, it is that the F.S.C. has had much greater success in wealthy Northern Hemisphere countries like Sweden, where \uc2 Tetra Pak\uc2  was founded in 1950, and in Canada, rather than in tropical countries where the need to protect forests is greatest.\par \par \uc2 The organization has had some success in the Republic of Congo and Gabon in Central Africa. And it certifies vast commercial plantations of trees in Brazil. These take some of the pressure off the cutting of tropical forests for paper, the organization believes.\par \par \uc2 Christoph Thies, a forest campaigner at \uc2 Greenpeace\uc2  in Hamburg, said that while the F.S.C. is the most rigorous of certifiers, it still has limitations as a conservation tool. The F.S.C\u8217\'20\'19s role is to improve forest management where logging has already been accepted, he said. What the F.S.C. cannot do is \u8216\'20\'18\u8216\'20\'18exclude large areas of valuable forest from logging,\u8217\'20\'19\u8217\'20\'19 he said. Such protection is needed in many regions, he added, but needs to come from governments \u8212\'20\'14 which often are not up to the job \u8212\'20\'14 not voluntary organizations.\par \par \uc2 He also worries that the growing demand from companies and consumers for F.S.C. certification could be causing its standards to slip. For instance, he said, the F.S.C. is \u8216\'20\'18\u8216\'20\'18not putting enough additional requirements on forest management\u8217\'20\'19\u8217\'20\'19 to preserve large intact areas of forest in places like Russia, Canada and the Congo basin.\par \par \uc2 Still, having an organization like the F.S.C. on the job seems better than not having one at all. About 99 percent of \uc2 Tetra Pak\uc2 \u8217\'20\'19s paper now comes from areas that have some level of certification from the F.S.C. Almost 40 percent of the company\u8217\'20\'19s supplies come from forest areas where the operators are held to stricter standards, like setting aside no-harvesting areas as natural forest, according to the company. \uc2 Tetra Pak\uc2 \u8217\'20\'19s suppliers are mainly based in Scandinavia, the United States, Russia and Brazil.\par \par \uc2 Companies say they are being forced to improve their environmental practices by their customers, who are increasingly insistent that the products they use be associated with environmentally responsible practices. Mr. Jonsson of \uc2 Tetra Pak\uc2  said being able to display the F.S.C. logo on packages is \u8216\'20\'18\u8216\'20\'18a competitive advantage.\u8217\'20\'19\u8217\'20\'19\par \par \uc2 Likewise, Mr. Siddiqui said \u8216\'20\'18\u8216\'20\'18we are seeing a greater interest in F.S.C. certified products\u8217\'20\'19\u8217\'20\'19 from \u8216\'20\'18\u8216\'20\'18institutional buyers like government agencies and large corporations.\u8217\'20\'19\u8217\'20\'19\par \par \uc2 Perhaps more than many people realize, blue-chip companies are responding to these pressures. \u8216\'20\'18\u8216\'20\'18I think these big companies like \uc2 Tetra Pak\uc2  and \uc2 Ikea\uc2  are doing a very good job. They are helping to set standards for some of the less progressive companies,\u8217\'20\'19\u8217\'20\'19 said Alison Hoare, a scholar at \uc2 Chatham House\uc2 , a London research institute.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\