FT articles and redistribute by email or post to the web.   \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Six of the world's leading insurers are to invest in a new $400m private equity fund being set up to back companies that sell financial services to individuals in developing countries.\par \par \uc2 MetLife\uc2 , \uc2 Prudential Financial\uc2  and \uc2 Swiss Re\uc2  are among the companies backing the second fund being put together by specialist "microfinance" house, Leapfrog Investments.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 The group will disclose as early as Monday that it has raised $204m for the venture, with plans to raise up to $200m more in the coming months.\par \par \uc2 Other investors include the financial institutions \uc2 JPMorgan Chase\uc2 , \uc2 TIAA-CREF\uc2  and the \uc2 European Investment Bank\uc2  as well as mainstream insurers such as Partner Re, XL and Achmea.\par \par \uc2 The fund will aim to take stakes in companies that offer general insurance and life assurance, as well as savings, pensions and investment products, to low-income consumers, some of whom earn between $1.25 and $10 a day.\par \par \uc2 It will be looking at prospective investments in south and south east Asian markets such as India, Indonesia and Sri Lanka as well as parts of sub Saharan Africa including Ghana, Nigeria and Kenya.\par \par \uc2 "A lot of people are saying the fundraising \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  is quite brutal," said Andrew Kuper, founder of Leapfrog. "But people [investors] are looking for operators [of businesses], not just clever [financial] structures.\par \par \uc2 "People have become interested in Africa, parts of Asia . . . We see decades of opportunity lying ahead."\par \par \uc2 Leading insurers based in developed markets have previously focused their expansion efforts in developing countries on the relatively prosperous emerging middle classes. They have tended to avoid the high volume, low margin and difficult business of offering financial services to the world's poorest people, especially given potential problems in distributing the products.\par \par \uc2 However, Leapfrog said mainstream insurers are increasingly interested in the area.\par \par \uc2 The tabular content relating to this article is not available to view. Apologies in advance for the inconvenience caused.\par \par \uc2 <>Lata Reddy, a \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  executive at \uc2 Prudential Financial\uc2 , said: "People have been slow in coming to the realisation there's potential in making money here. It's a shift in mindset - seeing low-income [individuals] as consumers, not recipients [of charitable aid]."\par \par \uc2 Leapfrog pointed to research from bodies including the \uc2 World Bank\uc2 , Global Findex and McKinsey showing there are 1.9bn potential consumers - only three in 10 of whom have access to financial services. Their total consumption is forecast to rise from $2tn to $5tn by 2022.\par \par \uc2 The new fund is set to become almost three times bigger than 